{"title_page": "Pierre Seginaud", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Pierre Seginaud\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| fullname      = Pierre Seginaud\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Pierre Seginaud''' was a French [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in three events at the [[1908 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/pierre-seginaud-1.html |title=Pierre Seginaud Olympic Results |accessdate=2 May 2013 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seginaud, Pierre}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Pierre Seginaud\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| fullname      = Pierre Seginaud\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Pierre Seginaud''' was a French [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in three events at the [[1908 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/pierre-seginaud-1.html |title=Pierre Seginaud Olympic Results |accessdate=2013-05-02 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seginaud, Pierre}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Seginaud"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Pitiscus", "text_new": "'''Samuel Pitiscus''' (30 March 1637, in [[Zutphen]] &ndash; 1 February 1727, in [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]<ref>http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=piti001</ref>) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] historian and classicist. He was a nephew of [[Bartholomaeus Pitiscus]].\n\n==Biography==\nSamuel Pitiscus was born in [[Zutphen]] as the son of a vicar. His parents were German immigrants coming from [[Palts]]. At age sixteen he studied theology in [[Deventer]] and transferred to Groningen in 1655 to continue his studies. Three years later he was appointed as headmaster of the Latin school in his home town. He held this post until 1685 when he accepted a similar position at the Latin school in [[Utrecht]]. In 1690 he was asked by a printer to deliver a commentary on the work of [[Suetonius]] and the book was published later that year. In 1713 he revised [[Johannes Rosinus|Rosinus']] work on [[ancient Rome|Roman]] antiquities, publishing his ''Lexicon antiquitatum romanarum''.   He also published a Dutch-Latin dictionary together with [[Arnoldus Henricus Westerhovius]]. Pitiscus retired in 1717\n\n==Works==\n*''Gaiji Suetonii Tranquilli Opera'' (1690)\n*''Lexicon antiquitatum Romanarum'' (1713)\n*''Lexicon Latino-Belgicum novum'' (1729, posthumously)\n\n==References==\n* E.O.G. Haitsma Mulier en G.A.C. van der Lem: ''Repertorium van geschiedschrijvers in Nederland 1500-1800''. Nederlands Historisch Genootschap, Den Haag 1990\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|de}} http://www.richardwolf.de/latein/pitiscus.htm\n*{{in lang|de}} [[:de:s:ADB:Pitiscus, Samuel]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitiscus, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1637 births]]\n[[Category:1727 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dutch classical scholars]]\n[[Category:People from Zutphen]]\n", "text_old": "'''Samuel Pitiscus''' (30 March 1637, in [[Zutphen]] &ndash; 1 February 1727, in [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]<ref>http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=piti001</ref>) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] historican and classicist. He was a nephew of [[Bartholomaeus Pitiscus]].\n\n==Biography==\nSamuel Pitiscus was born in [[Zutphen]] as the son of a vicar. His parents were German immigrants coming from [[Palts]]. At age sixteen he studied theology in [[Deventer]] and transferred to Groningen in 1655 to continue his studies. Three years later he was appointed as headmaster of the Latin school in his home town. He held this post until 1685 when he accepted a similar position at the Latin school in [[Utrecht]]. In 1690 he was asked by a printer to deliver a commentary on the work of [[Suetonius]] and the book was published later that year. In 1713 he revised [[Johannes Rosinus|Rosinus']] work on [[ancient Rome|Roman]] antiquities, publishing his ''Lexicon antiquitatum romanarum''.   He also published a Dutch-Latin dictionary together with [[Arnoldus Henricus Westerhovius]]. Pitiscus retired in 1717\n\n==Works==\n*''Gaiji Suetonii Tranquilli Opera'' (1690)\n*''Lexicon antiquitatum Romanarum'' (1713)\n*''Lexicon Latino-Belgicum novum'' (1729, posthumously)\n\n==References==\n* E.O.G. Haitsma Mulier en G.A.C. van der Lem: ''Repertorium van geschiedschrijvers in Nederland 1500-1800''. Nederlands Historisch Genootschap, Den Haag 1990\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|de}} http://www.richardwolf.de/latein/pitiscus.htm\n*{{in lang|de}} [[:de:s:ADB:Pitiscus, Samuel]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitiscus, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1637 births]]\n[[Category:1727 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dutch classical scholars]]\n[[Category:People from Zutphen]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Pitiscus"}
{"title_page": "Pierre Ruby", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierre Ruby\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1932|9|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bron]], France\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Pierre Ruby''' (born 20 September 1932) is a French former professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=14462 |title=Pierre Ruby |accessdate=12 July 2016 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He rode in five editions of the [[Tour de France]].<ref name=\"mdc1960\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=47\u00e8me Tour de France 1960|language=French|accessdate=11 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121063116/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|archivedate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling archives|14462}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruby, Pierre}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Bron]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierre Ruby\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1932|9|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bron]], France\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Pierre Ruby''' (born 20 September 1932) is a French former professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=14462 |title=Pierre Ruby |accessdate=12 July 2016 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He rode in five editions of the [[Tour de France]].<ref name=\"mdc1960\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=47\u00e8me Tour de France 1960|language=French|accessdate=11 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121063116/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|archivedate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling archives|14462}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruby, Pierre}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Bron]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Ruby"}
{"title_page": "Darya Mitina", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{one source|date=February 2014}}{{more footnotes|date=February 2014}}}}\n{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|\u041c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0414\u0430\u0440\u044c\u044f \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 |date=January 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Darya Mitina\n| native_name  = \u0414\u0430\u0440\u044c\u044f \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| honorific-suffix = [[State Duma|Member of Parliament]]\n| birthname    = Darya Alezandrovna Mitina\n| image        = Daria Mitina.jpg\n| caption      = \n| nationality  = [[Russian nationality|Russian]]\n| office       = Secretary of the Central Committee of the [[United Communist Party]]\n| term_start   = 6 February 2010 \n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = Position established\n| website = http://ucp.su/persons/oficialnaya-stranica-mitinoj-d/\n| office2      = First Secretary of the Central Committee of the [[Russian Young Communist League]] (RKSM)\n| term_start2  = 23 January 2001\n| term_end2    = \n| predecessor2 = [[Aleksey Pokatayev]]\n| successor2   = \n| office3      = \n| term_start3  = \n| term_end3    = \n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3   = \n| office4      = Member of the [[State Duma]]\n| term_start4  = 1995\n| term_end4    = 1999\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1973|8|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| spouse       = [[Said Gafurov]]\n| children     = \n| religion     = \n| profession   = \n| party        = [[United Communist Party]]\n| otherparty   = \n| signature    = \n| allegiance   = \n| branch       = \n| serviceyears = \n| rank         = \n| awards       = \n| alma_mater = [[Moscow State University|Moscow State University (1995)]]\n}}\n\nDarya Alexandrovna Mitina is a Russian leftist politician, historian, and cinema critic. She was born on August 14, 1973 in Moscow. Her mother, Natalia Mitina, was a known Soviet cinema scenario writer, and her father, Kasem Iskander Ibrahim Mohammed Yusufzai, was the founder of an [[Afghanistan]] national TV network. Her grandfather, [[Mohammad Yusuf (politician)|Mohammed Yusuf]], was the [[Prime Minister of Afghanistan]] from 1963 to 1965.<ref>\u041c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0451\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438: \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u044b \u0438 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0438 / \u0418. \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432, \u042e. \u0420\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0415. \u041b\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u0440. \u2014 \u041c.: \u0420\u041e\u041e \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0430\u00bb, 2007. \u0421. 134. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-94420-030-3}}. (I.Yakovlev, Yu Ryshkina, Ye. Loskutova. Political organisations of Youth:  Programs and People. Moscow. Panorama 2007)\n</ref> She is married to [[Said Gafurov]]. She graduated as a [[historian]] and [[ethnologist]] from the Faculty of History of the [[Moscow State University]] in 1995\n.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucp.su/persons/oficialnaya-stranica-mitinoj-d/|title=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0414.\u0410.|website=ucp.su|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n== Political activity ==\nSince 2014 she has been a Secretary responsible for International affairs of the Party <ref>http://ucp.su/persons/oficialnaya-stranica-mitinoj-d/</ref> and member of the Political commission of the [[United Communist Party]] (Russia).<ref>http://ucp.su/about/</ref>\n\nShe was a deputy of the [[State Duma]] for the second convocation (1995-1999). During the 2016 [[State Duma]] elections she was a candidate from the \"Communist Party \"[[Communists of Russia]]\"\" at the Cheremushkinskiy election district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nablawiki.ru/index.php/%D0%93%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%83%D0%B4%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B2%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%8F_%D0%B4%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B0,_18.09.2016:%D0%9C%D0%BE%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B2%D0%B0|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430, 18.09.2016:\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430\u0431\u043b\u044e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f|language=ru|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref> but did not succeed.\n\nShe is the First Secretary of the Central Committee of the Russian Communist Youth League ([[Komsomol]]), and she was one of its founders in 1993.\n\nIn May\u2013August 2014 Mitina was the Representative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] in Moscow.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n1. [http://kolobok1973.livejournal.com/ Darya Mitina blog]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitina, Darya}}\n[[Category:Russian Marxists]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian communists]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Afghan descent]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{one source|date=February 2014}}{{more footnotes|date=February 2014}}}}\n{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|\u041c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0414\u0430\u0440\u044c\u044f \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 |date=January 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Darya Mitina\n| native_name  = \u0414\u0430\u0440\u044c\u044f \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| honorific-suffix = [[State Duma|Member of Parliament]]\n| birthname    = Darya Alezandrovna Mitina\n| image        = Daria Mitina.jpg\n| caption      = \n| nationality  = [[Russian nationality|Russian]]\n| office       = Secretary of the Central Committee of the [[United Communist Party]]\n| term_start   = 6 February 2010 \n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = Position established\n| website = http://ucp.su/persons/oficialnaya-stranica-mitinoj-d/\n| office2      = First Secretary of the Central Committee of the [[Russian Young Communist League]] (RKSM)\n| term_start2  = 23 January 2001\n| term_end2    = \n| predecessor2 = [[Aleksey Pokatayev]]\n| successor2   = \n| office3      = \n| term_start3  = \n| term_end3    = \n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3   = \n| office4      = Member of the [[State Duma]]\n| term_start4  = 1995\n| term_end4    = 1999\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1973|8|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| spouse       = [[Said Gafurov]]\n| children     = \n| religion     = \n| profession   = \n| party        = [[United Communist Party]]\n| otherparty   = \n| signature    = \n| allegiance   = \n| branch       = \n| serviceyears = \n| rank         = \n| awards       = \n| alma_mater = [[Moscow State University|Moscow State University (1995)]]\n}}\n\nDarya Alexandrovna Mitina is a Russian leftist politician, historican, and cinema critic. She was born on August 14, 1973 in Moscow. Her mother, Natalia Mitina, was a known Soviet cinema scenario writer, and her father, Kasem Iskander Ibrahim Mohammed Yusufzai, was the founder of an [[Afghanistan]] national TV network. Her grandfather, [[Mohammad Yusuf (politician)|Mohammed Yusuf]], was the [[Prime Minister of Afghanistan]] from 1963 to 1965.<ref>\u041c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0451\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438: \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u044b \u0438 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0438 / \u0418. \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432, \u042e. \u0420\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0415. \u041b\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u0440. \u2014 \u041c.: \u0420\u041e\u041e \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0430\u00bb, 2007. \u0421. 134. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-94420-030-3}}. (I.Yakovlev, Yu Ryshkina, Ye. Loskutova. Political organisations of Youth:  Programs and People. Moscow. Panorama 2007)\n</ref> She is married to [[Said Gafurov]]. She graduated as a [[historian]] and [[ethnologist]] from the Faculty of History of the [[Moscow State University]] in 1995\n.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucp.su/persons/oficialnaya-stranica-mitinoj-d/|title=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0414.\u0410.|website=ucp.su|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n== Political activity ==\nSince 2014 she has been a Secretary responsible for International affairs of the Party <ref>http://ucp.su/persons/oficialnaya-stranica-mitinoj-d/</ref> and member of the Political commission of the [[United Communist Party]] (Russia).<ref>http://ucp.su/about/</ref>\n\nShe was a deputy of the [[State Duma]] for the second convocation (1995-1999). During the 2016 [[State Duma]] elections she was a candidate from the \"Communist Party \"[[Communists of Russia]]\"\" at the Cheremushkinskiy election district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nablawiki.ru/index.php/%D0%93%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%83%D0%B4%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B2%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%8F_%D0%B4%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B0,_18.09.2016:%D0%9C%D0%BE%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B2%D0%B0|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430, 18.09.2016:\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430\u0431\u043b\u044e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f|language=ru|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref> but did not succeed.\n\nShe is the First Secretary of the Central Committee of the Russian Communist Youth League ([[Komsomol]]), and she was one of its founders in 1993.\n\nIn May\u2013August 2014 Mitina was the Representative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] in Moscow.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n1. [http://kolobok1973.livejournal.com/ Darya Mitina blog]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitina, Darya}}\n[[Category:Russian Marxists]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian communists]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Afghan descent]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darya_Mitina"}
{"title_page": "Panthera leo melanochaita", "text_new": "{{Short description|Lion subspecies}}\n{{Subspeciesbox\n| name = ''{{PAGENAME}}''\n| image = Die pure Kraft - L\u00f6we im Etosha-Nationalpark.JPG\n| image_caption = Male lion in [[Etosha National Park]], Namibia\n| image2 = Lioness Samburu 2.jpg\n| image2_caption = Lioness in [[Samburu National Reserve]], Kenya\n| genus = Panthera\n| species = leo\n| species_link = lion\n| subspecies = melanochaita\n| authority = ([[Charles Hamilton Smith|Smith]], 1842)\n| synonyms =\n* ''P. l. bleyenberghi''\n* ''P. l. krugeri''\n* ''P. l. hollisteri''\n* ''P. l. massaica''\n* ''P. l. nyanzae''\n| synonyms_ref =<ref name=\"Catsg2017\"/>\n}}\n'''''Panthera leo melanochaita''''' is a [[lion]] [[subspecies]] in [[Southern Africa|Southern]] and [[East Africa]].<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O\u2019Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |volume=Special Issue 11 |pages=71\u221273 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y#page=71}}</ref> In this part of [[Africa]], lion populations are regionally [[locally extinct|extinct]] in [[Lesotho]], [[Djibouti]] and [[Eritrea]], and threatened by loss of habitat and prey base, killing by local people in retaliation for loss of livestock, and in several countries also by [[trophy hunting]].<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Panthera leo'' |author=Bauer, H. |author2=Packer, C. |author3=Funston, P.  F. |author4=Henschel, P. |author5=Nowell, K. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2016 |volume=2016 |page=e.T15951A115130419}}</ref> Since the turn of the 21st century, lion populations in intensively managed [[protected area]]s in Botswana, Namibia, South Africa and Zimbabwe have increased, but declined in East African range countries.<ref name=Bauer_al2015>{{cite journal |author1=Bauer, H. |author2=Chapron, G. |author3=Nowell, K. |author4=Henschel, P. |author5=Funston, P. |author6=Hunter, L. T. |author7=Macdonald, D. W. |author8=Packer, C. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2015 |title=Lion (''Panthera leo'') populations are declining rapidly across Africa, except in intensively managed areas |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=112 |issue=48 |pages=14894\u201314899 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/112/48/14894.full|doi=10.1073/pnas.1500664112 |pmid=26504235 |pmc=4672814 |bibcode=2015PNAS..11214894B}}</ref> In 2005, a Lion Conservation Strategy was developed for East and Southern Africa.<ref name=csg2006>{{cite book |author=IUCN Cat Specialist Group |year=2006 |title=Conservation Strategy for the Lion ''Panthera leo'' in Eastern and Southern Africa |publisher=IUCN |location=Pretoria, South Africa |url=http://www.catsg.org/fileadmin/filesharing/3.Conservation_Center/3.4._Strategies___Action_Plans/African_lion/IUCN_CatSG_2006_East_and_South_Africa_Lion_Conservation_Strategy.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe [[type specimen]] for ''P. l. melanochaita'' was a black-maned lion from the [[Cape of Good Hope]], known as the [[Cape lion]].<ref name=\"Mazak1975\">{{cite journal |author=Mazak, V. |year=1975 |title=Notes on the Black-maned Lion of the Cape, ''Panthera leo melanochaita'' (Ch. H. Smith, 1842) and a Revised List of the Preserved Specimens |journal=Verhandelingen Koninklijke Nederlandse Akademie van Wetenschappen |issue=64 |pages=1\u201344}}</ref> [[phylogeography|Phylogeographic]] analysis of lion samples from [[Gabon]] and the [[Republic of the Congo]] indicate their close genetic relation to ''P. l. melanochaita'' samples from [[Namibia]] and [[Botswana]].<ref name=Barnett_al2018>{{cite journal |author1=Barnett, R. |author2=Sinding, M. H. |author3=Vieira, F. G. |author4=Mendoza, M. L. |author5=Bonnet, M. |author6=Araldi, A. |author7=Kienast, I. |author8=Zambarda, A. |author9=Yamaguchi, N. |author10=Henschel, P. |author11=Gilbert, M. T. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2018 |title=No longer locally extinct? Tracing the origins of a lion (''Panthera leo'') living in Gabon |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=611\u2013618 |doi=10.1007/s10592-017-1039-2|pmid=31007636 |pmc=6448349}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |footer=Lions shot in Kenya's Sotik Plains in 1909 |image1=The Big Game of Africa (1910) - Lioness Sotik Plains 1909.png |image2=The Big Game of Africa (1910) - Male Lion Sotik Plains 1909.png}}\n''Felis (Leo) melanochaitus'' was the [[scientific name]] proposed by [[Charles Hamilton Smith]] in 1842 who described a lion specimen from South Africa's Cape Province.<ref name=Smith1842>{{cite book |author=Smith, C. H. |year=1842 |chapter=Black maned lion ''Leo melanochaitus'' |page=Plate X, 177 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/naturalistslibra15jardrich#page/176/mode/2up |title=The Naturalist's Library. Vol. 15 Mammalia |editor1-last=Jardine |editor1-first=W. |location=London |publisher=Chatto and Windus}}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several naturalists described [[zoological specimen]]s from Southern and East Africa and proposed the following subspecies:\n*''Felis leo somaliensis'' <small>(Noack 1891)</small>, based on two lion specimens from [[Somalia]]<ref name=Noack1891>{{cite journal |author=Noack, T. |year=1891 |title=''Felis leo'' |journal=Jahrbuch der Hamburgischen Wissenschaftlichen Anstalten |volume=9 |issue=1 |page=120 |url=}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo massaicus'' <small>([[Oscar Rudolph Neumann|Neumann]] 1900)</small>, based on two lions killed near [[Kibaya]] and the Gurui River in [[Kenya]]<ref name=Neumann>{{cite journal |author=Neumann, O. |year=1900 |title=Die von mir in den Jahren 1892\u201395 in Ost- und Central-Afrika, speciell in den Massai-L\u00e4ndern und den L\u00e4ndern am Victoria Nyansa gesammelten und beobachteten S\u00e4ugethiere |journal=Zoologische Jahrb\u00fccher. Abtheilung f\u00fcr Systematik, Geographie und Biologie der Thiere |volume=13 |issue=VI |pages=529\u2013562 |url=https://archive.org/stream/zoologischejahrb13jena#page/550/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo sabakiensis'' <small>([[Einar L\u00f6nnberg|L\u00f6nnberg]] 1910)</small>, based on two male lions from the environs of [[Mount Kilimanjaro]]<ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1910\">{{cite book |author=L\u00f6nnberg, E. |year=1910 |chapter=Mammals |title=Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Schwedischen Zoologischen Expedition nach dem Kilimandjaro, dem Meru und den umgebenden Massaisteppen Deutsch-Ostafrikas 1905\u20131906. Volume 1 |location=Stockholm |publisher=P. Palmquists Aktiebolag |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/wissenschaftlich01sj#page/n133/mode/2up |pages=1\u221258, Plate 1\u22127 |editor1-last=Sj\u00f6stedt |editor1-first=Y.}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo roosevelti'' <small>([[Edmund Heller|Heller]] 1913)</small>, a lion from the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] presented to [[Theodore Roosevelt]]<ref name=Heller>{{cite journal |author=Heller, E. |year=1913 |title=New races of carnivores and baboons from equatorial Africa and Abyssinia |journal=Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections |volume=61 |issue=19 |pages=1\u201312 |url=https://archive.org/stream/smithsonianmisce611914smit#page/n583/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo nyanzae'' <small>(Heller 1913)</small>, a lion skin from [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]<ref name=Heller/>\n*''Felis leo bleyenberghi'' <small>(L\u00f6nnberg 1914)</small>, a male lion from the [[Katanga Province]] of [[Belgian Congo]]<ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1914\">{{cite journal |author=L\u00f6nnberg, E. |year=1914 |title=New and rare mammals from Congo |journal=Revue de Zoologie Africaine |issue=3 |pages=273\u2013278 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revuezoologiquea03brux#page/272/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Leo leo hollisteri'' <small>([[Joel Asaph Allen]] 1924)</small>, a male lion from the area of [[Lime Springs, Sotik]] on the eastern shore of [[Lake Victoria]]<ref name=Allen1924>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J. A. |year=1924 |title=Carnivora Collected By The American Museum Congo Expedition |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=47 |pages=73\u2013281 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinamerican47ameruoft#page/223/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Leo leo krugeri'' <small>([[Austin Roberts (zoologist)|Austin Roberts]] 1929)</small>, an adult male lion from the [[Sabi Sand Game Reserve]] named in honour of [[Paul Kruger]]<ref name=Roberts1929>{{cite journal |author=Roberts, A. |year=1929 |title=New forms of African mammals |journal=Annals of the Transvaal Museum |volume=21 |issue=13 |pages=82\u2013121 |url=}}</ref>\n*''Leo leo vernayi'' <small>(Roberts 1948)</small>, a male lion from the [[Kalahari]] collected by the [[Arthur Stannard Vernay|Vernay]]-Lang Kalahari Expedition<ref name=Roberts1948>{{cite journal |author=Roberts, A. |year=1948 |title=Descriptions of some new subspecies of mammals |journal=Annals of the Transvaal Museum |volume=21 |issue=1 |pages=63\u201369 |url=}}</ref>\n*''Panthera leo webbensies'' <small>[[:de: Ludwig Zukowsky|Ludwig Zukowsky]] 1964</small>, two lions from [[Somalia]], one in the [[Natural History Museum, Vienna]] that originated in [[Shabeelle River|Webi Shabeelle]], the other kept in a German zoo that had been imported from the hinterland of [[Mogadishu]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Zukowsky, L. |year=1964 |title=Eine neue L\u00f6wenrasse als weiterer Beleg f\u00fcr die Verzwergung der Wirbeltierfauna des afrikanischen Osthorns |journal=Milu, Wissenschaftliche und Kulturelle Mitteilungen aus dem Tierpark Berlin |issue=1 |pages=269\u2013273}}</ref>\n\nDispute over the [[Valid name (zoology)|validity]] of these purported subspecies continued among naturalists and curators of [[natural history museum]]s until the early 21st century.<ref name=Mazak1975/><ref name=Allen1939>{{cite book |last=Allen |first=G. M. |year=1939 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofmuseum83harv#page/242/mode/2up |title=A Checklist of African Mammals |work=Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College |volume=83 |pages=1\u2013763|publisher=Cambridge, Mass. : The Museum }}</ref><ref name=\"Lundholm1952\">{{cite journal |author=Lundholm, B. |year=1952 |title=A skull of a Cape lioness (''Felis leo melanochaitus'' H. Smith |journal=Annals of the Transvaal Museum |issue=32 |pages=21\u201324}}</ref><ref name=Hemmer1974>{{cite journal |author=Hemmer, H. |year=1974 |title=Untersuchungen zur Stammesgeschichte der Pantherkatzen (''Pantherinae'') Teil 3. Zur Artgeschichte des L\u00f6wen ''Panthera (Panthera) leo'' (Linnaeus, 1758) |journal=Ver\u00f6ffentlichungen der Zoologischen Staatssammlung |volume=17| pages=167\u2013280 |url=https://archive.org/stream/verfentlichungen171974zool#page/178/mode/2up}}</ref><ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Carnivora |id=14000228 |page=546 |heading=''Panthera leo''}}</ref>\nIn the 20th century, some authors supported the view of the Cape lion being a distinct subspecies.<ref name=Roberts1929/><ref name=Allen1939/> In 1939, the American zoologist [[Glover Morrill Allen|Allen]] also recognized ''F. l. bleyenberghi'', ''F. l. krugeri'' and ''F. l. vernayi'' as [[Valid name (zoology)|valid]] subspecies in Southern Africa, and ''F. l. hollisteri'', ''F. l. nyanzae'' and ''F. l. massaica'' as valid subspecies in East Africa.<ref name=Allen1939/>\n \n[[Reginald Innes Pocock|Pocock]] subordinated the lion to the [[Genus (biology)|genus]] ''[[Panthera]]'' in 1930, when he wrote about [[Asiatic lion]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Pocock, R. I. |year=1930 |title=The lions of Asia |journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural Historical Society |volume=34 |issue= |pages=638\u2013665 |url=}}</ref> [[Sir John Ellerman, 2nd Baronet|Ellerman]] and [[Terence Morrison-Scott|Morrison-Scott]] recognized only two lion subspecies in the [[Palearctic realm]], namely the African ''P. l. leo'' and the Asiatic ''P. l. persica''.<ref name=\"EllermanMorrisonScott1966\">{{cite book |author1=Ellerman, J. R. |author2=Morrison-Scott, T. C. S. |year=1966 |title=Checklist of Palaearctic and Indian Mammals 1758 to 1946 |location=London |publisher=British Museum (Natural History) |page=319 |chapter=Subgenus ''Leo'' Oken, 1816, (Brehm, 1829) |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/checklistofindia00elle#page/318/mode/2up |edition=Second}}</ref> Various authors recognized between seven and 10 African lion subspecies.<ref name=Hemmer1974/> Others followed the [[Taxonomic classification|classification]] proposed by Ellerman and Morrison-Scott, recognizing two subspecies including one in Africa.<ref name=MeesterSetzer1977>{{cite book |author=Meester, J. |author2=Setzer, H. W. |year=1977 |title=The mammals of Africa. An identification manual |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |url=}}</ref>\n \nIn the 1970s, the scientific name ''P. l. vernayi'' was considered [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonym]]ous with ''P. l. krugeri''.<ref name=Hemmer1974/> In 1975, [[Vratislav Maz\u00e1k]] hypothesized that the Cape lion evolved geographically isolated from other populations by the [[Great Escarpment, Southern Africa|Great Escarpment]].<ref name=Mazak1975/> In the early 21st century, Maz\u00e1k's hypothesis about a geographically isolated evolution of the Cape lion was challenged. Genetic exchanges between populations in the Cape, Kalahari and [[Transvaal Province]] regions and farther east are considered having been possible through a corridor between the Great Escarpment and the [[Indian ocean]].<ref name=Yamaguchi2000>{{cite journal |author=Yamaguchi, N. |year=2000 |url=http://www.tigertouch.org/documents/barbarycape.pdf |title=The Barbary lion and the Cape lion: their phylogenetic places and conservation |journal=African Lion Working Group News |volume=1 |pages=9\u201311}}</ref><ref name=Barnett2006>{{cite journal |author1=Barnett, R. |author2=Yamaguchi, N. |author3=Barnes, I. |author4=Cooper, A. |year=2006 |url=http://abc.zoo.ox.ac.uk/Papers/consgen06_lion.pdf |title=Lost populations and preserving genetic diversity in the lion ''Panthera leo'': Implications for its ex situ conservation |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=507\u2013514 |doi=10.1007/s10592-005-9062-0 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2006-08-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824064412/http://abc.zoo.ox.ac.uk/Papers/consgen06_lion.pdf }}</ref>\n \nIn 2005, the authors of ''[[Mammal Species of the World]]'' recognized ''P. l. bleyenberghi'', ''P. l. krugeri'', ''P. l. vernayi'', ''P. l. massaica'', ''P. l. hollisteri'' and ''P. l. nyanzae'' as valid [[Taxon|taxa]].<ref name=MSW3/> In 2016, [[IUCN Red List]] assessors subsumed all African lion populations to ''P. l. leo''.<ref name=iucn/> Two lion subspecies are now recognised:<ref name=Catsg2017/>\n*''P. l. melanochaita'' is understood as comprising lion populations in the contemporary Southern and East African range countries,\n*[[Panthera leo leo|''P. l. leo'']] comprises lion populations in North, West and Central Africa and Asia.\n \n=== Phylogeny ===\n[[File:Lion subspecies distribution3.png|thumb|Range map including proposed clades and the two subspecies (''P. l. leo'' and ''P. l. melanochaita'') according to genetic research]]\nSince the beginning of the 21st century, several [[phylogenetic]] studies were conducted to aid clarifying the [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic status]] of lion samples kept in museums and collected in the wild. Scientists analysed between 32 and 480 lion samples from up to 22 countries. Results of [[genetic analyses]] indicate that the [[Species (biological)|species]] comprises two main [[evolution]]ary groups, one in Southern and East Africa, and the other in the northern and eastern parts of its historical range.<ref name=\"Barnett_al2006Origin\">{{Cite journal |last1=Barnett |first1=R. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Barnes |first3=I. |last4=Cooper |first4=A. |year=2006 |title=The origin, current diversity and future conservation of the modern lion (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |pmid=16901830 |volume=273 |issue=1598 |pmc=1635511 |pages=2119\u20132125 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2006.3555 |url=http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acad/publications/papers/Barnett%20PRS%20lions.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808182526/http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acad/publications/papers/Barnett%20PRS%20lions.pdf |archive-date=8 August 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Dubach_al2005\">{{Cite journal |last=Dubach |first=J. |last2=Patterson |first2= B. D. |last3=Briggs |first3=M. B. |last4=Venzke |first4=K. |last5=Flamand |first5=J. |last6=Stander |first6=P. |last7=Scheepers |first7=L. |last8=Kays |first8=R. W. |date=2005 |title=Molecular genetic variation across the southern and eastern geographic ranges of the African lion, ''Panthera leo'' |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=15\u201324 |doi=10.1007/s10592-004-7729-6 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226066591}}</ref><ref name=\"Agostinho_al2008\">{{Cite journal |author=Antunes, A. |author2=Troyer, J. L. |author3=Roelke, M. E. |author4=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author5=Packer, C. |author6=Winterbach, C. |author7=Winterbach, H. |author8=Johnson, W. E. |title=The Evolutionary Dynamics of the Lion ''Panthera leo'' revealed by Host and Viral Population Genomics |journal=PLOS Genetics |volume=4 |issue=11 |pages=e1000251 |year=2008 |pmid=18989457 |pmc=2572142 |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1000251}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |authors=Dubach, J. M., Briggs, M. B., White, P. A., Ament, B. A., & Patterson, B. D. |year=2013 |title=Genetic perspectives on \"Lion Conservation Units\" in Eastern and Southern Africa |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=741\u2212755 |doi=10.1007/s10592-013-0453-3}}</ref> These groups [[Genetic divergence|genetically diverged]] between 50,000 and 200,000 years ago.<ref name=\"O'Brienetal1987\">{{cite journal |author=O\u2019Brien, S. J. |author2=Martenson, J. S. |author3=Packer, C. |author4=Herbst, L. |author5=de Vos, V. |author6=Joslin, P. |author7=Ott-Joslin, J. |author8=Wildt, D. E. |author9=Bush, M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1987 |title=Biochemical genetic variation in geographic isolates of African and Asiatic lions |url=http://www.cbs.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/downloads/Biochemical_Genetic_Variation_in_Geographic_Isolates_of_African_and_Asiatic_Lions.pdf |journal=National Geographic Research |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=114\u2013124 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502101107/http://www.cbs.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/downloads/Biochemical_Genetic_Variation_in_Geographic_Isolates_of_African_and_Asiatic_Lions.pdf |archive-date=2013-05-02}}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2016/> It was assumed that [[tropical rainforest]] and the [[East African Rift]] constituted major barriers between the two groups.<ref name=Barnett2006/><ref name=\"Agostinho_al2008\"/><ref name=\"Mazak2010\">{{cite journal |author=Maz\u00e1k, J. H. |year=2010 |title=Geographical variation and phylogenetics of modern lions based on craniometric data |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=281 |issue=3 |pages=194\u2212209}}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2011>{{Cite journal |last1=Bertola |first1=L. D. |last2=Van Hooft |first2=W. F. |last3=Vrieling |first3=K. |last4=Uit De Weerd |first4=D. R. |last5=York |first5=D. S. |last6=Bauer |first6=H. |last7=Prins |first7=H. H. T. |last8=Funston |first8=P. J. |last9=Udo De Haes |first9=H. A. |last10=Leirs |first10=H. |last11=Van Haeringen |first11=W. A. |last12=Sogbohossou |first12=E. |last13=Tumenta |first13=P. N. |last14=De Iongh |first14=H. H. |title=Genetic diversity, evolutionary history and implications for conservation of the lion (''Panthera leo'') in West and Central Africa |journal=[[Journal of Biogeography]] |volume=38 |issue=7 |pages=1356\u20131367 |year=2011 |url=http://dspace.learningnetworks.org/bitstream/1820/4311/1/2011_Bertola,Hooft,Vrieling,Weerd,York,Bauer,Prins,Haes,Iongh_GeneticDiversityEvolutionaryHistoryAndImplicationsForConservationOfTheLionInWestAndCentralAfrica.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2699.2011.02500.x |access-date=2018-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608070014/http://dspace.learningnetworks.org/bitstream/1820/4311/1/2011_Bertola,Hooft,Vrieling,Weerd,York,Bauer,Prins,Haes,Iongh_GeneticDiversityEvolutionaryHistoryAndImplicationsForConservationOfTheLionInWestAndCentralAfrica.pdf |archive-date=2019-06-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2015>{{cite journal |authors=Bertola, L. D., Tensen, L., Van Hooft, P., White, P. A., Driscoll, C. A., Henschel, P., Caragiulo, A., Dias-Freedman, I., Sogbohossou, E. A., Tumenta, P. N. and Jirmo, T. H. |year=2015 |title=Autosomal and mtDNA markers affirm the distinctiveness of lions in West and Central Africa |journal=PLOS One |volume=10 |issue=10 |page=e0137975 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0137975|pmid=26466139 |pmc=4605676 |bibcode=2015PLoSO..1037975B }}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2016>{{cite journal |author=Bertola, L. D. |author2=Jongbloed, H. |author3=Van Der Gaag, K. J. |author4=De Knijff, P. |author5=Yamaguchi, N. |author6=Hooghiemstra, H. |author7=Bauer, H. |author8=Henschel, P. |author9=White, P. A. |author10=Driscoll, C. A. |author11=Tende, T. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2016 |title=Phylogeographic patterns in Africa and High Resolution Delineation of genetic clades in the Lion (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Scientific Reports |volume=6 |page=30807 |doi=10.1038/srep30807|pmid=27488946 |pmc=4973251 |bibcode=2016NatSR...630807B}}</ref>\n\nLion samples from Gabon's [[Bat\u00e9k\u00e9 Plateau National Park]] and [[Odzala-Kokoua National Park]] in Republic of the Congo were found to be genetically closely related to lion samples from Namibia and Botswana.<ref name=Barnett_al2018/>\n\n=== Overlap between subspecies ===\n[[File:Annual report - New York Zoological Society (1914) (18433145331).jpg|thumb|Lion from Ethiopia at [[Bronx Zoo]]]]\nAmong six samples of captive lions from Ethiopia, five clustered with samples from East Africa, but one with samples from the [[Sahel]].<ref name=Bertola_al2011/> For a subsequent [[phylogeographic]] study, eight wild lion samples from the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] were included in the [[DNA sequencing]] analysis using 194 lion samples from 22 countries. Four of these samples [[Cluster (statistics)|cluster]]ed with samples from Central Africa, and four with samples from East Africa, indicating that the [[Great Rift Valley, Ethiopia]] was not a complete barrier to [[gene flow]]. Southeastern Ethiopia is therefore considered a [[genetic admixture]] zone between Central and East African lions.<ref name=Bertola_al2016/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n|image1=Lion_cubs,_Zimbabwe_(5213422527).jpg |caption1=Lion cubs in Zimbabwe\n|image2=Lions on rock-2.jpg |caption2=Adult male lions in [[Serengeti National Park]]\n|image3=Male panthera leo Kenya 07 (cropped).jpg |caption3=Male lion in [[Narok County]]\n}}\nThe lion's fur varies in colour from light buff to dark brown. It has rounded ears and a black tail tuft.<ref name=Guggisberg1975>{{cite book |last=Guggisberg |first=C. A. W. |chapter=Lion ''Panthera leo'' (Linnaeus, 1758) |title=Wild Cats of the World |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00gugg |chapter-url-access=registration |year=1975 |publisher=Taplinger Publishing |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8008-8324-9 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00gugg/page/138 138\u2013179]}}</ref>\n\n=== Manes ===\nIn the 19th and 20th centuries, lion [[type specimen]]s were described on the basis of their mane size and colour. Mane colour varies from sandy, tawny, isabelline, light reddish yellow to dark brown and black.<ref name=Smith1842/><ref name=Heller/><ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1914\"/><ref name=\"Guggisberg1963\">{{cite book |author=Guggisberg, Charles Albert Walter |title=Simba: The Life of the Lion |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4eTaAAAAMAAJ |year=1963 |publisher=Chilton Books |location=Philadelphia, PA |page= |asin=B000OKBJQ0}}</ref><ref name=Smithers1971>{{cite book |last=Smithers |first=R. H. N. |year=1971 |title=The Mammals of Botswana |publisher=University of Pretoria |location=Pretoria |chapter=Panthera leo |pages=116\u2212119}}</ref> Mane length varies from short to extending to knee joints and under the belly.<ref name=Hemmer1974/>\nLions without a mane were observed in the Tsavo area.<ref name=\"Borzo2002\"/>\n\nMane development is related to age: older males have more extensive manes than younger ones; manes continue to grow up to the age of four to five years, long after lions become [[sexually mature]]. Males living in the highlands above altitudes of {{convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}} develop heavier manes than lions in the more humid and warmer lowlands of eastern and northern Kenya. The latter have thinner manes, or are even [[maneless lion|maneless]].<ref name=\"Gnoskeetal2006\">{{cite journal |author1=Gnoske, T. P. |author2=Celesia, G. G. |author3=Kerbis Peterhans, J. C. |year=2006 |title=Dissociation between mane development and sexual maturity in lions (''Panthera leo''): solution to the Tsavo riddle? |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=270 |issue=4 |pages=551\u2013560 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00200.x |bibcode=2010JZoo..281..263G}}</ref> Hence, lion manes reflect ambient temperature. Mane colour is also influenced by nutrition and [[testosterone]]. Its length is an indicator for age and fighting ability of the lion.<ref name=\"WestPacker2002\">{{Cite journal |author1=West, P. M. |author2=Packer, C. |date=2002 |title=Sexual Selection, Temperature, and the Lion's Mane |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=297 |issue=5585 |pages=1339\u20131943 |doi=10.1126/science.1073257 |pmid=12193785 |bibcode=2002Sci...297.1339W}}</ref>\n\n=== Size and weight ===\nAverage head-to-body length of male lions is {{convert|2.47|-|3.14|m|ft|abbr=on}} with an average weight of {{convert|190|-|313|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in Southern Africa and {{convert|191.9-319|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in East Africa. Females average {{convert|122.2|-|165.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in Southern Africa and {{convert|119.5-161.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in East Africa.<ref name=Smuts_etal_1980>{{cite journal |author1=Smuts, G. L. |author2=Robinson, G. A. |author3=Whyte, I. J. |title=Comparative growth of wild male and female lions (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Journal of Zoology |year=1980 |volume=190 |issue=3 |pages=365\u2013373 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1980.tb01433.x |bibcode=2010JZoo..281..263G}}</ref>\nMales in Kruger National Park weighed {{convert|210.01|and|276.55|kg|lb|abbr=on}} on average, whereas females weighed {{convert|153.52|and|121.37|kg|lb|abbr=on}} on average, though there was an outbreak of [[tuberculosis]] in the park at the time.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keet |first1=D. F. |last2=Kriek |first2=N. P. J. |last3=Mills |first3=M. G. L. |title=The epidemiology of tuberculosis in free-ranging lions in the Kruger National Park |publisher=[[South African National Parks]] |year=1999 |access-date=2019-08-13 |url=https://www.sanparks.org/parks/kruger/conservation/scientific/projects/Project_Reports_PDF/73.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe largest known lion measured {{convert|3.35|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Guggisberg1975\"/> An exceptionally heavy male lion near [[Mount Kenya National Park|Mount Kenya]] weighed {{convert|322|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"NowellJackson1996\">{{cite book |author1=Nowell, K. |author2=Jackson, P. |chapter=African lion |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |chapterurl=http://carnivoractionplans1.free.fr/wildcats.pdf |year=1996 |publisher=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |location=Gland, Switzerland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |pages=17\u201321}}</ref> The longest wild lion reportedly was a male shot near [[Mucusso National Park]] in southern Angola in 1973. In 1936, a [[man-eating]] lion shot in 1936 in eastern Transvaal weighed about {{convert|343|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and was considered to have been one of heaviest wild lions. <ref name=Wood1983>{{cite book |last=Wood |first=G. L. |year=1982 |title=The Guinness Book of Animal Facts and Feats |location=Enfield, Middlesex |edition=Third |publisher=Guinness Superlatives Ltd. |isbn=978-0-85112-235-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessbookofan00wood}}</ref> In 1963, two lions in Tanzania weighed {{convert|355.5|kg|lbs|order=flip|abbr=on}} and {{convert|394|kg|lbs|order=flip|abbr=on}} after killing [[livestock]].<ref name=\"UPA1963\">{{cite book |work=University Press of Africa, with contributions from the Kenya National Chamber of Commerce & Industry |title=East African Business Digest |url=https://books.google.com/?id=i_JPAQAAIAAJ |year=1963 |access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== White lion ===\n{{Main|White lion}}\n[[File:Kruger Cub.jpg|thumb|A cub in Kruger National Park]]\nWhite lions have occasionally been encountered in and around South Africa's [[Kruger National Park]] and the adjacent [[Timbavati Private Game Reserve]]. Their whitish fur is a rare [[Polymorphism (biology)|morph]] caused by a double [[Dominance (genetics)|recessive]] [[allele]]. It has normal pigmentation in eyes and skin. They were removed from the wild in the 1970s, thus decreasing the white lion [[gene pool]]. Nevertheless, 17 births have been recorded in five different prides between 2007 and 2015.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Turner |first1=J. A. |last2=Vasicek |first2=C. A. |last3=Somers |first3=M. J. |year=2015 |title=Effects of a colour variant on hunting ability: the white lion in South Africa |journal=Open Science Repository Biology |page=e45011830}}</ref> White lions were selected for breeding in [[captivity (animal)|captivity]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=McBride |first=C. |title=The White Lions of Timbavati |year=1977 |publisher=E. Stanton |location=[[Johannesburg]] |isbn=978-0-949997-32-6}}</ref> They have been bred in South African camps for use as trophies to be killed during [[canned hunt]]s.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Tucker |first=L. |title=Mystery of the White Lions\u2014Children of the Sun God |year=2003 |publisher=Npenvu Press |location=[[Mapumalanga]] |isbn=978-0-620-31409-1}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |image1=Lion_cubs_Serengeti.jpg |image2=7 lions.jpg |image3=Lionesses with cubs, Selous Game Reserve (28) (28436353633).jpg |footer=The Serengeti and Maasai Mara National Parks and Selous Game Reserve are lion strongholds in East Africa with stable lion populations<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>}}\nIn East and Southern Africa, lion populations declined in:\n*[[Somalia]] since the early 20th century.<ref name=\"FunaioliSimonetta1966\">{{cite journal |author=Funaioli, U. and Simonetta, A. M. |year=1966 |title=The Mammalian Fauna of the Somali Republic: Status and Conservation Problems |journal=Monitore Zoologico Italiano, Supplemento |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=285\u2013347 |doi=10.1080/03749444.1966.10736746}}</ref> Intensive [[poaching]] since the 1980s and civil unrest posed a threat to lion persistence.<ref name=Chardonnet2002>{{cite book |author=Chardonnet, P. |year=2002 |title=Conservation of the African Lion : Contribution to a Status Survey |location=Paris |publisher=International Foundation for the Conservation of Wildlife, France & Conservation Force, USA |chapter=Chapter II: Population Survey |pages=21\u2013101 |chapterurl=http://conservationforce.org/pdf/conservationoftheafricanlion.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110184540/http://conservationforce.org/pdf/conservationoftheafricanlion.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Fagotto1985\">{{cite journal |author=Fagotto, F. |year=1985 |title=Larger animals of Somalia in 1984 |journal=Environmental Conservation |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=260\u2212264|doi=10.1017/S0376892900016015}}</ref>\n*[[Uganda]] to near extinction in the 20th century.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Treves, A. |author2=Naughton-Treves, L. |year=1999 |title=Risk and opportunity for humans coexisting with large carnivores |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=275\u2212282 |doi=10.1006/jhev.1998.0268 |pmid=10074384|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/68f322bacfaa9cbbb282b23865499b6bd99a9301 }}</ref> In 2010, the lion population in Uganda was estimated at 408 \u00b1 46 individuals in three protected areas including Queen Elizabeth, Murchison Falls and Kidepo Valley National Parks. Other protected areas in the country probably host less than 10 lions.<ref name=Omoya_al2014>{{cite journal |author1=Omoya, E. O. |author2=Mudumba, T. |author3=Buckland, S. T. |author4=Mulondo, P. |author5=Plumptre, A. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2014 |title=Estimating population sizes of lions ''Panthera leo'' and spotted hyaenas ''Crocuta crocuta'' in Uganda's savannah parks, using lure count methods |journal=Oryx |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=394\u2013401 |doi=10.1017/S0030605313000112 |url=https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/10023/6885/omoya2014oryx394.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref> Lions in [[Queen Elizabeth National Park]] form a contiguous population with lions in [[Virunga National Park]].<ref name=Treves_al2009>{{cite journal |author1=Treves, A. |author2=Plumptre, A. J. |author3=Hunter, L. T. B. |author4=Ziwa, J. |year=2009 |title=Identifying a potential lion ''Panthera leo'' stronghold in Queen Elizabeth National Park, Uganda, and Parc National des Virunga, Democratic Republic of Congo |journal=Oryx |volume=43 |pages=60\u221266 |doi=10.1017/S003060530700124X}}</ref>\n*[[Kenya]] in the 1990s due to poisoning of lions and poaching of lion prey species.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/> At least 108 lions were killed between 2001 and 2006 in the [[Amboseli National Park|Amboseli]]\u2212[[Tsavo West National Park|Tsavo West]]\u2212[[Tsavo East National Park]] network.<ref name=Frank_al2006>{{cite book |author1=Frank, L.  |author2=Maclennan, S. |author3=Hazzah, L. |author4=Hill, T. |author5=Bonham, R. |year=2006 |title=Lion Killing in the Amboseli-Tsavo Ecosystem, 2001\u20132006, and its Implications for Kenya's Lion Population |publisher=Living with Lions |location=Nairobi |url=http://www.livingwithlions.org/AnnualReports/2006-Lion-killing-in-Amboseli-Tsavo-ecosystem.pdf}}</ref> As of 2006, there were an estimated 675 lions in the Tsavo national parks, out of the 2,000 total in Kenya.<ref name=Frank_al2006/> Between 2004 and 2013, lion guardians around Amboseli National Park identified 65 lions in an area of {{convert|3684|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dolrenry, S. |author2=Hazzah, L. |author3=Frank, L. G. |year=2016 |title=Conservation and monitoring of a persecuted African lion population by Maasai warriors |volume=30 |journal=Conservation Biology |issue=3 |pages=467\u2212475 |doi= 10.1111/cobi.12703|pmid=27111059}}</ref> Lion populations in Kenya and Tanzania are fragmented over 17 patches ranging in size from {{convert|86|to|127515|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dolrenry, S. |author2=Stenglein, J. |author3=Hazzah, L. |author4=Lutz, R. S. |author5=Frank, L. |year=2014 |title=A metapopulation approach to African lion (''Panthera leo'') conservation |journal= PLOS One |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=e88081 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0088081 |pmid=24505385 |pmc=3914926 |bibcode=2014PLoSO...988081D}}</ref>\n*[[Rwanda]] and [[Tanzania]] due to killing of lions during the [[Rwandan Civil War]] and ensuing [[Great Lakes refugee crisis|refugee crisis]] in the 1990s.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/> A small population was present in Rwanda's [[Akagera National Park]], estimated at 35 individuals at most in 2004.<ref name=Bauer_vanderMerwe>{{Cite journal |last1=Bauer |first1=H. |last2=Van Der Merwe |first2=S. |doi=10.1017/S0030605304000055 |title=Inventory of free-ranging lions ''Panthera leo'' in Africa |journal=Oryx |volume=38 |year=2004 |issue=1 |pages=26\u201331}}</ref> Lions were reintroduced to this national park in 2015.<ref>{{cite thesis |author=Bantlin, D. A. |year=2017 |title=Movements of Reintroduced Lions in Akagera National Park, Rwanda, in Relation to Prey Abundance |type=Doctoral dissertation |publisher=University of Wisconsin\u2212Madison |location=Madison}}</ref>\n*[[Malawi]] and [[Zambia]] due to illegal hunting of prey species in protected areas.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/>\n*[[Botswana]] due to intensive hunting and conversion of natural habitats for settlements since the early 19th century.<ref name=Smithers1971/> In Northern Tuli Game Reserve, 19 lions died between 2005 and 2011 due to poaching, trophy hunting and [[Trapping#Snares|snaring]].<ref name=Snyman2015>{{cite journal |author1=Snyman, A.  |author2=Jackson, C. R. |author3=Funston, P. J. |year=2015 |title=The effect of alternative forms of hunting on the social organization of two small populations of lions ''Panthera leo'' in Southern Africa |volume=49 |journal=Oryx |issue=4 |pages=604\u2212610 |doi=10.1017/S0030605313001336}}</ref>\n*[[Namibia]] due to massive killing of lions by farmers since at least the 1970s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Stander, P. E. |year=1990 |title=A suggested management strategy for stock-raiding lions in Namibia |journal=South African Journal of Wildlife Research |volume=20 |issue=2|pages=37\u221243}}</ref> In 2010, the small and isolated lion population in the [[Kalahari]] was estimated at 683 to 1,397 individuals in three protected areas, the [[Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park]], the [[Kalahari Gemsbok National Park|Kalahari Gemsbok]] and [[Gemsbok National Park]]s.<ref name=Ferreira_al2013>{{cite journal |author1=Ferreira, S. M. |author2=Govender, D. |author3=Herbst, M. |year=2013 |title=Conservation implications of Kalahari lion population dynamics |journal=African Journal of Ecology |volume=51 |issue=2 |pages=176\u2013179|doi=10.1111/aje.12003}}</ref>\n*[[South Africa]] since the early 19th century in the [[Natal Province|Natal]] and [[Cape Province]]s south of the [[Orange River]], where the Cape lion population was eradicated by 1860.<ref name=Mazak1975/> A few decades later, lions in the [[Highveld]] north of the Orange River were also eradicated.<ref name=\"Guggisberg1975\"/> In [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]], lions occurred historically in the Highveld as well, but were restricted to eastern Transvaal's [[Bushveld]] by the 1970s.<ref>{{cite book |author=Rautenbach, I. L. |year=1978 |title=The Mammals of the Transvaal |publisher=University of Natal |location=[[Pietermaritzburg]] |chapter=''Panthera leo'' (Linnaeus, 1758) |pages=471\u2212475}}</ref> Between 2000 and 2004, 34 lions were reintroduced to eight protected areas in the [[Eastern Cape Province]], including [[Addo Elephant National Park]].<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Hayward, M. W., Adendorff, J., O\u2019Brien, J., Sholto-Douglas, A., Bissett, C., Moolman, L. C., Bean, P., Fogarty, A., Howarth, D., Slater, R. and Kerley, G. I. |year=2007 |title=Practical considerations for the reintroduction of large, terrestrial, mammalian predators based on reintroductions to South Africa's Eastern Cape Province |volume=1 |journal=The Open Conservation Biology Journal |issue=1 |pages=1\u221211 |doi=10.2174/1874839200701010001 |url=http://benthamopen.com/contents/pdf/TOCONSBJ/TOCONSBJ-1-1.pdf}}</ref> In [[Venetia Limpopo Nature Reserve]], 18 lions were trophy hunted and 11 [[euthanized]] between 2005 and 2011.<ref name=Snyman2015/>\n\nContemporary lion distribution and habitat quality in East and Southern Africa was assessed in 2005, and Lion Conservation Units (LCU) mapped.<ref name=csg2006/> Between 2002 and 2012, educated guesses for size of populations in these LCUs ranged from 33,967 to 32,000 individuals.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/><ref name=Riggioetal2013>{{cite journal |author1=Riggio, J. |author2=Jacobson, A. |author3=Dollar, L. |author4=Bauer, H. |author5=Becker, M. |author6=Dickman, A. |author7=Funston, P. |author8=Groom, R. |author9=Henschel, P. |author10=De Iongh, H. |author11=Lichtenfeld, L. |year=2013 |title=The size of savannah Africa: a lion's (''Panthera leo'') view |journal=Biodiversity and Conservation |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201335 |doi=10.1007/s10531-012-0381-4}}</ref>\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- valign=bottom\n! Range countries !! Lion Conservation Units !! Area in km<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|Democratic Republic of Congo ||[[Massif D'itombwe]], [[Luama River|Luama]] ||8,441<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Democratic Republic of Congo, Uganda ||Queen Elizabeth\u2212Virunga National Parks ||5,583<ref name=Treves_al2009/>\n|-\n|Uganda ||[[Toro-Semliki Wildlife Reserve|Toro\u2212Semulik]], [[Lake Mburo National Park|Lake Mburo]], [[Murchison Falls National Park|Murchison Falls]] ||4,800<ref>{{cite book |author1=Mudumba, T. |author2=Mulondo, P. |author3=Okot, E. |author4=Nsubuga, M. |author5=Plumptre, A. |year=2009 |title= National Census of Lions and Hyaenas in Uganda. Strategic Action Plan for Large Carnivore Conservation in Uganda |location=Kampala |publisher=[[Uganda Wildlife Authority]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|Somalia ||[[Lower Shabelle|Arboweerow\u2212Alafuuto]] ||24,527<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Somalia, Kenya ||[[Lag Badana National Park|Bushbush]]\u2212[[Arawale National Reserve|Arawale]]||22,540<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Kenya ||[[Laikipia County|Laikipia]]\u2212[[Samburu National Reserve|Samburu]], [[Meru National Park|Meru]] and [[Nairobi National Park]]s ||43,706<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Kenya, Tanzania ||[[Serengeti National Park|Serengeti]]\u2212[[Maasai Mara National Reserve|Mara]] and [[Tsavo East National Park|Tsavo]]\u2212[[Mkomazi National Park|Mkomazi]] ||75,068<ref name=Mesochina2010>{{cite book |author1=M\u00e9sochina, P. |author2=Mbangwa, O. |author3=Chardonnet, P. |author4=Mosha, R. |author5=Mtui, B. |author6=Drouet, N. |author7=Kissui, B. |year=2010 |title=Conservation status of the lion (''Panthera leo'' Linnaeus, 1758) in Tanzania |location=[[Paris]] |publisher=SCI Foundation, MNRT-WD, TAWISA & IGF Foundation}}</ref>\n|-\n|Tanzania ||Dar-[[Biharamulo Game Reserve|Biharamulo]], [[Ruaha National Park|Ruaha]]\u2212[[Rungwa Game Reserve|Rungwa]], [[Mpanga-Kipengere Game Reserve|Mpanga-Kipengere]], [[Tarangire National Park|Tarangire]], [[Wami River|Wami]] Mbiki\u2212[[Saadani National Park|Saadani]], [[Selous Game Reserve|Selous]] ||384,489<ref name=Mesochina2010/>\n|-\n|Tanzania, Mozambique ||[[Niassa Reserve|Niassa]] ||177,559<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009>{{cite book |author1=Chardonnet, P. |author2=M\u00e9sochina, P. |author3=Bento, C. |author4=Conjo, D. |author5=Begg, C. l. |year=2009 |title=Conservation status of the lion (''Panthera leo'' Linnaeus, 1758) in Mozambique |location=Maputo, Mozambique |publisher=Fondation IGF, Campfire Association, SCI Foundation, The Ratel Trust, Direc\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional de Terras e Florestas |url=https://agritrop.cirad.fr/550720/1/document_550720.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n|Mozambique ||[[Cahora Bassa]], [[Gil\u00e9 District|Gil\u00e9]], [[Gorongosa National Park|Gorongosa]]\u2212[[Marromeu District|Marromeu]] ||82,715<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009/>\n|-\n|Mozambique, Zambia ||[[Zambezi#Middle Zambezi|Middle Zambezi]] ||64,672<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009/>\n|-\n|Mozambique, South Africa ||[[Great Limpopo Transfrontier Park]] ||150,347<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009/>\n|-\n|Zambia ||[[Liuwa Plain National Park|Liuwa Plains]], [[Sioma Ngwezi National Park|Sioma Ngwezi]], [[Kafue National Park|Kafue Sumbu Complex]] ||72,569<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Zambia, Malawi ||[[North Luangwa National Park|North]]\u2212[[South Luangwa National Park|South Luangwa]]||72,992<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Malawi ||[[Kasungu National Park|Kasungu]], [[Nkhotakota Wildlife Reserve|Nkhotakota]] ||4,187<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Zimbabwe ||[[Mapungubwe National Park|Mapungubwe]], [[Bubye River|Bubye]] ||10,033<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Botswana, Zimbabwe ||[[Okavango Delta|Okavango]]\u2212[[Hwange National Park|Hwange]] ||99,552<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Botswana ||[[Moremi Game Reserve|Xaixai]] ||12,484<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Botswana, South Africa ||[[Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park|Kgalagadi]] ||163,329<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Angola ||[[Qui\u00e7ama National Park|Kissama]]\u2212Mumbondo, [[Benguela Province|Bocoio]]\u2212[[Camacuio]], [[Alto Zambeze]] ||393,760<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Angola, Namibia ||[[Etosha National Park|Etosha]]\u2212[[Kunene Region|Kunene]] ||123,800<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Namibia ||[[Khaudum National Park|Khaudum]]\u2212[[Caprivi Game Park|Caprivi]] ||92,372<ref name=csg2006/>\n|}\n \nThe LCUs Ruaha\u2212Rungwa, Serengeti\u2212Mara, Tsavo\u2212Mkomazi and Selous in East Africa, as well as Luangwa, Kgalagadi, Okavango\u2212Hwange, Mid\u2212Zambezi, Niassa and Greater Limpopo in Southern Africa are currently considered lion strongholds. These LCUs host more than 500 individuals each, and the population trend is stable there as of 2012.<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n\n== Behaviour and ecology ==\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n|image1=FrontLines_Environment_Photo_Contest_Winner_-7_(5809039672).jpg |caption1=Tree-climbing lion in Murchison Falls National Park\n|image2=Zimbabwe 4888bb.jpg |caption2=Lion pride at the [[Zambezi]] River\n|image3=Mating Lion, Etosha National Park, Namibia.jpg |caption3=Lions mating in Etosha National Park\n|image4=690V3740 - Flickr - Lip Kee.jpg |caption4=A lioness with her cub in Botswana}}\nIn [[Serengeti National Park]], monitoring of lion prides started in 1966.<ref name=Schaller72>{{Cite book |last=Schaller |first=G. B. |authorlink=George Schaller |year=1972 |title=The Serengeti lion: A study of predator\u2013prey relations |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |isbn=978-0-226-73639-6}}</ref>\nBetween 1966 and 1972, two observed lion prides comprised between seven and 10 females each. Females had litters once in 23 months on average.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Bertram, B.C.R. |year=1973 |title=Lion population regulation |journal=East African Wildlife Journal |volume=11 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=215\u2212225|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1973.tb00088.x }}</ref>\nLitters contained two to three cubs. Of 87 cubs born until 1970, only 12 reached the age of two years. Cubs died due to starvation in months when large prey was not available, or following take-over of the prides by new males.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Bertram, B. |year=1975 |title=Social factors influencing reproduction in wild lions |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=177 |issue=4 |pages=463\u2013482|doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1975.tb02246.x }}</ref> Male lions in coalitions are closely related.<ref name=Bygott1979>{{cite journal |authors=Bygott, J. D., Bertram, B. C. R., and Hanby, J. P. |year=1979 |title=Male lions in large coalitions gain reproductive advantages |journal=Nature |volume=282 |issue=5741 |pages=839\u2013841|bibcode=1979Natur.282..839B |doi=10.1038/282839a0 }}</ref>\nBetween 1974 and 2012, 471 coalitions comprising 796 male lions entered a study area of {{convert|2000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. Of these, 35 coalitions included male lions that were born in the area but had left and returned after about two years of absence. Nomadic coalitions became resident at between 3.5 and 7.3 years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Borrego, N. |author2=Ozgul, A. |author3=Slotow, R. |author4=Packer, C. |year=2018 |title=Lion population dynamics: do nomadic males matter? |journal=Behavioral Ecology |volume=29 |issue=3 |doi=10.1093/beheco/ary018 |pages=660\u2013666 |url=}}</ref>\n\nThe lion population of Selous Game Reserve has been surveyed since 1996. Lion prides avoided [[acacia]] woodlands and preferred habitats near water courses with short grasses, where also prey species gathered. Two or more prides shared home ranges.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Spong, G. |year=2002 |title=Space use in lions, ''Panthera leo'', in the Selous Game Reserve: social and ecological factors |journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |volume=52 |issue=4 |pages=303\u2013307 |doi=10.1007/s00265-002-0515-x}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Kavango\u2013Zambezi Transfrontier Conservation Area]], lions have been monitored since 1999. In 2003, 50 lions were [[Radio telemetry|radio-collared]] in [[Hwange National Park]] and tracked until 2012. Results show that adult male and female lions preferred grassland and [[shrubland]] habitat, but avoided woodlands and areas with high human density. By contrast, subadult [[biological dispersal|dispersing]] male lions avoided grasslands and shrublands, but moved in human-dominated areas to a larger extent. Hence, dispersing lions are more vulnerable to coming into [[Human\u2013wildlife conflict|conflict]] with humans than adult lions.<ref name=Elliot_al2014>{{cite journal |author1=Elliot, N. B. |author2=Cushman, S. A. |author3=Macdonald, D. W. |author4=Loveridge, A. J. |year=2014 |title=The devil is in the dispersers: predictions of landscape connectivity change with demography |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=1169\u20131178 |doi=10.1111/1365-2664.12282}}</ref>\nIn the semi-arid savanna of Zimbabwe's Hwange National Park, 19 lions were radio-collared and tracked between 2002 and 2007. Both female and male lions moved foremost within {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} of waterholes in all seasons.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Valeix, M., Loveridge, A. J., Davidson, Z., Madzikanda, H., Fritz, H. and Macdonald, D. W. |year=2010 |title=How key habitat features influence large terrestrial carnivore movements: waterholes and African lions in a semi-arid savanna of north-western Zimbabwe |volume=25 |journal=Landscape Ecology |issue=3 |pages=337\u2013351 |doi=10.1007/s10980-009-9425-x}}</ref>\n\nLions living near ranches in the vicinity of Tsavo East National Park consisted of three prides, two pairs and a single lion in 2002.<ref name=Patterson_al2004>{{cite journal |author=Patterson, B. D., Kasiki, S. M., Selempo, E. and Kays, R. W. |year=2004 |title=Livestock predation by lions (''Panthera leo'') and other carnivores on ranches neighboring Tsavo National Parks, Kenya |volume=119 |journal=Biological Conservation |issue=4 |pages=507\u2212516 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2004.01.013 |citeseerx=10.1.1.884.8117 }}</ref>\n\n=== Hunting and diet ===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n|image1=Lions hunting Africa.jpg |caption1=Lionesses hunting a Cape buffalo in the Okavango Delta\n|image2=Tinga 2012 05 20 0951 (7407622938).jpg |caption2=Lions feeding on a giraffe in Kruger National Park\n}}\nLions usually [[Cooperative hunting|hunt in groups]] and [[prey]] foremost on [[ungulate]]s such as [[gemsbok]] (''Oryx gazella''), [[Cape buffalo]] (''Syncerus caffer''), [[blue wildebeest]] (''Connochaetes taurinus''), [[giraffe]] (''Giraffa camelopardalis''), [[common eland]] (''Tragelaphus oryx''), [[greater kudu]] (''T. strepsiceros''), [[nyala]] (''T. angasii''), [[roan antelope]] (''Hippotragus equinus''), [[sable antelope]] (''H. niger''), [[plains zebra]] (''Equus quagga''), [[bushpig]] (''Potamochoerus larvatus''), [[common warthog]] (''Phacochoerus africanus''), [[hartebeest]] (''Alcephalus buselaphus''), [[common tsessebe]] (''Damaliscus lunatus''), [[waterbuck]] (''Kobus ellipsiprymnus''), [[kob]] (''K. kob'') and [[Thomson's gazelle]] (''Eudorcas thomsonii''). Their prey is usually in the range of {{convert|190|-|550|kg|lb|abbr=in}}.<ref name=Hayward2005>{{Cite journal |last1=Hayward |first1=M. W. |last2=Kerley |first2=G. I. H. |year=2005 |title=Prey preferences of the lion (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=267 |issue=3 |pages=309\u2013322 |doi=10.1017/S0952836905007508 |url=http://www.zbs.bialowieza.pl/g2/pdf/1595.pdf |bibcode=2010JZoo..281..263G |citeseerx=10.1.1.611.8271}}</ref> In the Serengeti National Park, lions were observed to also [[Scavenger|scavenge]] on [[carrion]] of animals that were killed by other predators, or died from natural causes. They kept a constant lookout for circling vultures, apparently being aware that vultures indicate a dead animal.<ref name=Schaller72/>\nFaeces of lions collected near waterholes in Hwange National Park also contained remains of climbing mice (''[[Dendromus]]'') and common mice (''[[Mus (genus)|Mus]]'').<ref>{{cite journal |author=Davidson, Z., Valeix, M., Van Kesteren, F., Loveridge, A.J., Hunt, J.E., Murindagomo, F. and Macdonald, D.W. |year=2013 |title=Seasonal diet and prey preference of the African lion in a waterhole-driven semi-arid savanna |volume=8 |journal=PLOS One |issue=2 |pages=e55182 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0055182.g001|pmid=23405121 |pmc=3566210 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...855182D }}</ref>\n \nIn Botswana's [[Chobe National Park]], lions also prey on [[African bush elephant]]s (''Loxodonta africana''). They successfully attacked 74 elephants between 1993 and 1996, of which 26 were older than nine years, and one bull over 15 years old.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Joubert |first1=D. |year=2006 |title=Hunting behaviour of lions (''Panthera leo'') on elephants (''Loxodonta africana'') in the Chobe National Park, Botswana |journal= African Journal of Ecology |volume=44 |issue=2 |pages=279\u2013281 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.2006.00626.x}}</ref> In October 2005, a pride of up to 30 lions killed eight African bush elephants that were between four and eleven years old.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Power |first1=R. J. |last2=Compion |first2=R. X. S. |title=Lion predation on elephants in the Savuti, Chobe National Park, Botswana |journal=African Zoology |volume=44 |issue=1 |pages=36\u201344 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232693088 |doi=10.3377/004.044.0104 |year=2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Attacks on humans ===\nSeveral cases of lion attacking people have been documented:\n*In the 1890s, two [[Tsavo Man-Eaters]] attacked workers during the building of the [[Uganda Railway]]. Their [[skull]]s and [[skin]]s are part of the zoological collection of the [[Field Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kerbis Peterhans, J. C. and Gnoske, T. P. |year=2001 |title=The Science of 'Man-Eating*' Among Lions ''Panthera leo'' With a Reconstruction of the Natural History of the 'Man-Eaters of Tsavo' |journal=Journal of East African Natural History |issue=1 |pages=1\u201340 |doi=10.2982/0012-8317(2001)90[1:TSOMAL]2.0.CO;2 |volume=90}}</ref> The total number of people killed is unclear, but allegedly 135 people fell victim to these lions in less than a year before [[John Henry Patterson (author)|Colonel Patterson]] killed them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Patterson |first=J. H. |author-link=John Henry Patterson (author) |year=1907 |url=https://archive.org/details/maneatersoftsavo00pattiala |title=The man-eaters of Tsavo and other East African adventures |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Macmillan and Co.]]}}</ref>\n* The Njombe lions were a lion pride in [[Njombe]] in former [[Tanganyika]], which are thought to have preyed on 1,500 to 2,000 people. They were killed by [[George Gilman Rushby]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Rushby |first=G. G. |title=No More the Tusker |year=1965 |publisher=W. H. Allen |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wneBAAAAIAAJ}}</ref>\n*Between 1990 and 2004, lions killed more than 560 people in Tanzania, mostly during harvest season in crop fields and in areas where natural prey is scarce.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Packer, C., Ikanda, D., Kissui, B. and Kushnir, H. |year=2005 |title=Lion attacks on humans in Tanzania |volume=436 |issue=7052 |journal=Nature |pages=927\u2212928 |doi=10.1038/436791a |pmid=16094358 |bibcode=2005Natur.436..791S |url=https://www.cbs.umn.edu/sites/cbs.umn.edu/files/public/downloads/Lion_attacks_on_humans_in_Tanzania.pdf}}</ref>\n* In February 2018, lions killed a suspected poacher near Kruger National Park.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=The [[BBC]] |title=South African lions eat 'poacher', leaving just his head |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43035474 |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Haden, A. |title=Suspected poacher mauled to death by lions close to Kruger National Park |publisher=The South African |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/suspected-poacher-killed-by-lions/ |date=2018 |access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* In February 2018, [[Kevin Richardson (zookeeper)|Kevin Richardson]] took three lions for a walk at Dinokeng Game Reserve in South Africa. A lioness pursued an impala for at least {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}}, and  killed a young woman near her car.<ref>{{cite news |author=Torchia, C. |title=Lion kills woman at refuge of South African 'lion whisperer' |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/lion-kills-woman-at-refuge-of-south-african-lion-whisperer/2018/02/28/f1630a0c-1c6b-11e8-98f5-ceecfa8741b6_story.html |date=2018 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n* In July 2018, human remains were found in the lion enclosure of a privately owned reserve in South Africa. They were suspected to have been rhino poachers, as they had a high-powered rifle with a silencer, an axe and [[wire cutter]]s.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[BBC News|BBC]] |title=Lions eat 'rhino poachers' on South African game reserve |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44728507 |date=2018 |access-date=2018-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |image1=Taxidermy Lion Trophy Seized by U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Miami (37402001470).jpg |caption1=Taxidermied lion trophy seized by U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service in 2017}}\nIn Africa, lions are threatened by pre-emptive killing or in retaliation for preying on livestock. Prey base depletion, loss and conversion of habitat have led to a number of subpopulations becoming small and isolated. [[Trophy hunting]] has contributed to population declines in Botswana, Namibia, Zimbabwe and Zambia.<ref name=iucn/> It is the primary cause for a decline of lion populations in Tanzania's Selous Game Reserve and [[Katavi National Park]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Packer, C. |author2=Brink, H. |author3=Kissui, B. M. |author4=Maliti, H. |author5=Kushnir, H. |author6=Caro, T. |year=2011 |title=Effects of trophy hunting on lion and leopard populations in Tanzania |journal=Conservation Biology |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=142\u2013153 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2010.01576.x|pmid=20825444 }}</ref> Although lions and their prey are officially protected in Tsavo National Parks, they are regularly killed by local people, with over 100 known lion killings between 2001 and 2006.<ref name=\"Frank_al2006\"/>\n \nBetween 2008 and 2013, bones and body parts from at least 2621 individual lions were exported from South Africa to [[Southeast Asia]], and another 3437 lion skeletons between 2014 and 2016. Lion bones are used to replace [[tiger]] bones in [[traditional Asian medicine]]s.<ref name=\"Williams_al2017\">{{cite journal |author1=Williams, V. L. |author2=Loveridge, A. J. |author3=Newton, D. J. |author4=Macdonald, D. W. |title=A roaring trade? The legal trade in ''Panthera leo'' bones from Africa to East-Southeast Asia |journal=PLOS One |volume=12 |issue=10 |page=e0185996 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0185996 |pmid=29065143 |pmc=5655489 |bibcode=2017PLoSO..1285996W |year=2017}}</ref> Private game ranches in South Africa also breed lions for the [[canned hunt]]ing industry.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Schroeder |first=R. A. |year=2018 |title=Moving Targets: The 'Canned'Hunting of Captive-Bred Lions in South Africa |journal=African Studies Review |volume=61 |issue=1 |pages=8\u201332 |doi=10.1017/asr.2017.94}}</ref>\n \nIn 2014, seven lions in Ikona Wildlife Management Area were reportedly poisoned by a herdsman for attacking his [[cattle]].<ref name=\"Cable2018\">{{cite news |newspaper=The Cable |title='Herdsmen' poison lions, vultures \u2014 but not in Nigeria |url=https://www.thecable.ng/herdsmen-poison-lions-vultures-not-nigeria |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref> In February 2018, the carcasses of two male and four female lions were found dead in Ruaha National Park, and were suspected to have died of poisoning.<ref name=\"Observer2018\">{{cite news |author=Kamoga, J. |title=East African lions dying of poisoning |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |url=http://observer.ug/lifestyle/57009-east-african-lions-dying-of-poisoning.html |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref><ref name=\"Express2018\">{{cite news |author=Winter, S. |title=Lion MASSACRE as six big cats die after eating 'poison' |newspaper=[[Daily Express]] |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/nature/920088/lion-massacre-conservationists-poison-africa-Ruaha-National-Park |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref>\n \nIn 2015 and 2017, two male lions, [[Cecil (lion)|Cecil]] and his son Xanda, were killed by trophy hunters in Zimbabwe's Hwange National Park.<ref name=\"BBC2015Cecil\">{{cite news |date=2015 |accessdate=3 August 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33674087 |title=Zimbabwe's 'iconic' lion Cecil killed by hunter |work=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728220149/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33674087 |archivedate=28 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Xanda, son of Cecil the lion, killed by hunter in Zimbabwe |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-40671590 |date=2017 |accessdate=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n \nUncontrolled bushfires and hunting of lions and prey species in Zambia's Kafue National Park make it difficult for the lion population to recover. Cub mortality in particular is high.<ref name=\"Midlane2013\">{{cite book |author=Midlane, N. |year=2013 |title=The conservation status and dynamics of a protected African lion ''Panthera leo'' population in Kafue National Park, Zambia |publisher=University of Cape Town |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |image1=500px photo (177037413).jpeg |caption1=Lion cubs in Botswana}}\nAfrican lions are included in [[CITES Appendix II]]. Today, lion populations are stable only in large protected area complexes.<ref name=iucn/> [[IUCN]] regional offices and many wildlife conservation organisations cooperated to develop a Lion Conservation Strategy for Eastern and Southern Africa in 2006. The strategy envisages to maintain sufficient habitat, ensure a sufficient wild prey base, make lion-human coexistence sustainable and reduce factors that lead to further fragmentation of populations.<ref name=csg2006/>\nLocal communities in several Southern African lion range countries generate significant income through [[wildlife tourism]], which is a strong incentive for their support of conservation measures.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nEstablishing corridors between protected areas is important for facilitating dispersal of lions. [[Makgadikgadi Pans National Park]] and [[Central Kalahari Game Reserve]] are key dispersal areas in Southern Africa.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Cushman, S. A. |author2=Elliot, N. B. |author3=Bauer, D. |author4=Kesch, K. |author5=Bahaa-el-din, L. |author6=Bothwell, H. |display-authors=etal |year=2018 |title=Prioritizing core areas, corridors and conflict hotspots for Lion conservation in Southern Africa |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=13 |issue=7 |pages=e0196213 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0196213|pmid=29975694 |bibcode=2018PLoSO..1396213C }}</ref>\n\n=== In captivity ===\n{{multiple image |perrow=1\n|image1=MP-panthera leo krugeri 5.jpg |caption1=Captive lion in [[Philadelphia Zoo]]}}\n[[File:LionWalk.jpg|thumb|right|Tourist petting tame lions, [[Livingstone]], [[Zambia]]]]\nAt the beginning of the 21st century, the [[Addis Ababa Zoo]] kept 16 adult lions. It is assumed that their ancestors, five males and two females, were caught in southwestern Ethiopia as part of a zoological collection for Emperor [[Haile Selassie of Ethiopia|Haile Selassie I]].<ref name=Brucheetal2012>{{Cite journal |last=Bruche |first=S. |author2=Gusset, M. |author3=Lippold, S. |author4=Barnett, R. |author5=Eulenberger, K. |author6=Junhold, J. |author7=Driscoll, C. A. |author8= Hofreiter, M. |title=A genetically distinct lion (''Panthera leo'') population from Ethiopia |journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research |year=2012 |pages=215\u2013225 |doi=10.1007/s10344-012-0668-5 |volume=59 |issue=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Tefera |first=M. |title=Phenotypic and reproductive characteristics of lions (''Panthera leo'') at Addis Ababa Zoo |journal=Biodiversity & Conservation |volume=12 |issue=8 |pages=1629\u20131639 |year=2003 |doi=10.1023/A:1023641629538}}</ref>\n \nIn 2006, eight captive lions were registered under the name ''P. l. massaicus'', and 23 as ''P. l. nubicus'' from Tanzania by the [[International Species Information System]]; about 100 captive lions were registered  as ''P. l. krugeri'', which derived from lions captured in South Africa.<ref name=\"Barnett2006\"/>\n\nIn 2012, samples of lions kept at [[Sana'a Zoo]] in [[Yemen]] were found to cluster with those of lions from East and Southern Africa.<ref name=\"Bruche_al2012\">{{Cite journal |last=Bruche |first=S. |author2=Gusset, M. |author3=Lippold, S. |author4=Barnett, R. |author5=Eulenberger, K. |author6=Junhold, J. |author7=Driscoll, C. A. |author8=Hofreiter, M. |title=A genetically distinct lion (''Panthera leo'') population from Ethiopia |journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research |year=2012 |pages=215\u2013225 |doi=10.1007/s10344-012-0668-5 |volume=59 |issue=2}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural significance==\n[[File:Coat of Arms of the South African Republic.png|thumb|120px|The [[Coat of arms of South Africa]] featured a lion from 1910 to 1932]]\nThe lion is an animal symbol in [[shamanistic]] rituals of the [[Nuer people]]. In other East African cultures, it symbolizes laziness.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hogarth |first=C. |last2=Butler |first2=N. |year=2004 |title=Shamanism: An Encyclopedia of World Beliefs, Practices, and Culture, Volume 1 |editor=Walter, M. N. |isbn=978-1-57607-645-3 |chapter=Animal Symbolism (Africa) |pages=[https://archive.org/details/shamanism00mari/page/3 3\u20136] |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=X8waCmzjiD4C&pg=PA3&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj916XT2OjjAhWG16QKHaj5A6kQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&f=false |url=https://archive.org/details/shamanism00mari/page/3 }}</ref> Scars inflicted by lions are regarded as a sign of courage among the [[Masai people]].<ref name=\"Lynch2004\">{{cite book |last=Lynch |first=P. A. |year=2004 |title=African Mythology A to Z |publisher=Infobase Publishing |page=[https://archive.org/details/africanmythology00lync_0/page/63 63] |isbn=978-0-8160-4892-2 |chapter=Lion |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/africanmythology00lync_0/page/63 |url=https://archive.org/details/africanmythology00lync_0/page/63 }}</ref>\nThe name '[[Simba]]' is a [[Swahili language|Swahili]] word for the lion, which also means 'aggressive', 'king' and 'strong'.<ref>{{cite book |author=Brakefield, T. |title=Big Cats: Kingdom of Might |publisher=Voyageur Press |url=https://archive.org/details/bigcatskingdomof0000brak |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/bigcatskingdomof0000brak/page/44 44] |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-89658-329-0}}</ref>\n\n==Regional names==\nLion populations in Southern and East Africa were referred to by several regional names, including Katanga lion, Transvaal lion, Kalahari lion,<ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1914\" /><ref name=Roberts1929/><ref name=Roberts1948/> Southeast African lion, and Southwest African lion,<ref name=\"Jackson2010\">{{cite book |last=Jackson |first=D. |title=Lion |chapter=Introduction |pages=1\u201321 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=65lK7UIVRfIC&pg |publisher=[[Reaktion Books]] |location=[[London]] |isbn=978-1861897350 |date=2010}}</ref> Masai lion, Serengeti lion,<ref name=Schaller72/> Tsavo lion<ref name=\"Borzo2002\">{{cite news |last=Borzo |first=G. |title=Unique social system found in famous Tsavo lions |url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2002-04/fm-uss040802.php |newspaper=EurekAlert |year=2002}}</ref> and Uganda lion.<ref name=Hemmer1974/> It has also been referred to as 'Eastern-Southern African lion',<ref name=\"Barnett_al2006Origin\"/> 'Southern lion',<ref name=\"Agostinho_al2008\"/> and as 'southern subspecies'.<ref name=\"Hunter2018\">{{cite book |last1=Hunter |first1=L. |author-link=Luke Hunter |last2=Barrett |first2=P. |title=The Field Guide to Carnivores of the World |edition=Second |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London, Oxford, New York, New Delhi, Sydney |isbn=978-1-4729-5080-2 |date=2018 |chapter=Lion ''Panthera leo'' |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4HpxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&f=false |pages=46\u221247}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*Wild cats in Africa: [[African leopard]] {{\u00b7}} [[African golden cat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Caracal]] {{\u00b7}} [[Serval]] {{\u00b7}} [[African wildcat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Sand cat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Black-footed cat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Cheetah]]\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Elsa the lioness]]\n*''[[Born Free]]''\n*[[Mapogo lion coalition]]\n*''[[The Lion King]]''\n*''[[Pride (2004 film)]]''\n*''[[African Cats]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n \n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Lions of Southern Africa}}\n{{Commons category|Lions of Southeast Africa}}\n*{{cite news |author=Carrington, D. |date=2018 |title=Lion poaching: the brutal new threat to Africa's prides |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/nov/05/lion-poaching-the-brutal-new-threat-to-africas-prides}}\n*{{cite web |title=Lion (''Panthera leo'' ssp. ''melanochaita'') |year=2016 |website=ECOS Environmental Conservation Online System |url=https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?sId=9519}}\n*[http://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Fund-to-stop-the-decline-in-the-population-of-African-lions/4552908-4587534-pty9m/index.html $0.5m funding to stop the decline in the population of African lions]\n*[https://africageographic.com/blog/what-will-it-take-to-save-the-east-african-lion-from-extinction-hunting-or-herding/ What Will It Take to Save the East African Lion from Extinction? Hunting or Herding?]\n*[http://leofoundation.org/en/projects/lions-in-east-africa/ Lions in East Africa]\n*[https://phys.org/news/2018-02-recovering-population-zimbabwean-african-lions.html Recovering population of Zimbabwean African lions show low genetic diversity]\n*[https://petapixel.com/2018/09/04/lioness-steals-photographers-canon-dslr-and-gives-it-to-her-cubs/ PetaPixel, September 2018: Lioness Steals Photographer\u2019s Canon DSLR and Gives It to Her Cubs]\n*[https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2018/06/wildlife-watch-illegal-trade-lions-teeth-claws-poaching/ National Geographic Wildlife Watch, June 2018: As Tigers Become Rarer, Poachers Are Targeting Lions]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/17/game-farmer-lion-protecting-home-robbers/ Lobengula the South African guardian lion]\n*[https://www.panthera.org/blog/2017/06/15/what-happened-angolas-1000-lions What Happened to Angola\u2019s 1,000 Lions?]\n*[https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2017/02/20/holding-the-line-for-lions-in-mozambique/ Holding the line for lions in Mozambique]\n*[http://www.iflscience.com/plants-and-animals/giant-lions-once-prowled-east-africa-200000yearold-skull-reveals/ Giant Lions Once Prowled East Africa, 200,000-Year-Old Skull Reveals]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q2ZW0EvMzSM BBC Earth: Lions take down an adult elephant]\n*[https://traveladventuresbotswana.com/the-savuti-lions-of-the-chobe-national-park/ The Savuti Lions of the Chobe National Park]\n*[https://www.smithsonianmag.com/photocontest/detail/natural-world/a-zambian-lion-stirs/ A Zambian lion stirs]\n*[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dramatic-video-shows-shamba-the-lion-mauling-animal-sanctuary-owner-in-south-africa/ Shamba the South African lion]\n*[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/escapes-south-african-lion-father-57798623 Known for escapes, South African lion becomes a father]\n \n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2118614}}\n\n[[Category:Lions]]\n[[Category:Subspecies]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1842]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Angola]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Botswana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Eswatini]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Somalia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Fauna of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Southern Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1843]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1891]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1900]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Lion subspecies}}\n{{Subspeciesbox\n| name = ''{{PAGENAME}}''\n| image = Die pure Kraft - L\u00f6we im Etosha-Nationalpark.JPG\n| image_caption = Male lion in [[Etosha National Park]], Namibia\n| image2 = Lioness Samburu 2.jpg\n| image2_caption = Lioness in [[Samburu National Reserve]], Kenya\n| genus = Panthera\n| species = leo\n| species_link = lion\n| subspecies = melanochaita\n| authority = ([[Charles Hamilton Smith|Smith]], 1842)\n| synonyms =\n* ''P. l. bleyenberghi''\n* ''P. l. krugeri''\n* ''P. l. hollisteri''\n* ''P. l. massaica''\n* ''P. l. nyanzae''\n| synonyms_ref =<ref name=\"Catsg2017\"/>\n}}\n'''''Panthera leo melanochaita''''' is a [[lion]] [[subspecies]] in [[Southern Africa|Southern]] and [[East Africa]].<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O\u2019Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |volume=Special Issue 11 |pages=71\u221273 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y#page=71}}</ref> In this part of [[Africa]], lion populations are regionally [[locally extinct|extinct]] in [[Lesotho]], [[Djibouti]] and [[Eritrea]], and threatened by loss of habitat and prey base, killing by local people in retaliation for loss of livestock, and in several countries also by [[trophy hunting]].<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Panthera leo'' |author=Bauer, H. |author2=Packer, C. |author3=Funston, P.  F. |author4=Henschel, P. |author5=Nowell, K. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2016 |volume=2016 |page=e.T15951A115130419}}</ref> Since the turn of the 21st century, lion populations in intensively managed [[protected area]]s in Botswana, Namibia, South Africa and Zimbabwe have increased, but declined in East African range countries.<ref name=Bauer_al2015>{{cite journal |author1=Bauer, H. |author2=Chapron, G. |author3=Nowell, K. |author4=Henschel, P. |author5=Funston, P. |author6=Hunter, L. T. |author7=Macdonald, D. W. |author8=Packer, C. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2015 |title=Lion (''Panthera leo'') populations are declining rapidly across Africa, except in intensively managed areas |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=112 |issue=48 |pages=14894\u201314899 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/112/48/14894.full|doi=10.1073/pnas.1500664112 |pmid=26504235 |pmc=4672814 |bibcode=2015PNAS..11214894B}}</ref> In 2005, a Lion Conservation Strategy was developed for East and Southern Africa.<ref name=csg2006>{{cite book |author=IUCN Cat Specialist Group |year=2006 |title=Conservation Strategy for the Lion ''Panthera leo'' in Eastern and Southern Africa |publisher=IUCN |location=Pretoria, South Africa |url=http://www.catsg.org/fileadmin/filesharing/3.Conservation_Center/3.4._Strategies___Action_Plans/African_lion/IUCN_CatSG_2006_East_and_South_Africa_Lion_Conservation_Strategy.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe [[type specimen]] for ''P. l. melanochaita'' was a black-maned lion from the [[Cape of Good Hope]], known as the [[Cape lion]].<ref name=\"Mazak1975\">{{cite journal |author=Mazak, V. |year=1975 |title=Notes on the Black-maned Lion of the Cape, ''Panthera leo melanochaita'' (Ch. H. Smith, 1842) and a Revised List of the Preserved Specimens |journal=Verhandelingen Koninklijke Nederlandse Akademie van Wetenschappen |issue=64 |pages=1\u201344}}</ref> [[phylogeography|Phylogeographic]] analysis of lion samples from [[Gabon]] and the [[Republic of the Congo]] indicate their close genetic relation to ''P. l. melanochaita'' samples from [[Namibia]] and [[Botswana]].<ref name=Barnett_al2018>{{cite journal |author1=Barnett, R. |author2=Sinding, M. H. |author3=Vieira, F. G. |author4=Mendoza, M. L. |author5=Bonnet, M. |author6=Araldi, A. |author7=Kienast, I. |author8=Zambarda, A. |author9=Yamaguchi, N. |author10=Henschel, P. |author11=Gilbert, M. T. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2018 |title=No longer locally extinct? Tracing the origins of a lion (''Panthera leo'') living in Gabon |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=611\u2013618 |doi=10.1007/s10592-017-1039-2|pmid=31007636 |pmc=6448349}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |footer=Lions shot in Kenya's Sotik Plains in 1909 |image1=The Big Game of Africa (1910) - Lioness Sotik Plains 1909.png |image2=The Big Game of Africa (1910) - Male Lion Sotik Plains 1909.png}}\n''Felis (Leo) melanochaitus'' was the [[scientific name]] proposed by [[Charles Hamilton Smith]] in 1842 who described a lion specimen from South Africa's Cape Province.<ref name=Smith1842>{{cite book |author=Smith, C. H. |year=1842 |chapter=Black maned lion ''Leo melanochaitus'' |page=Plate X, 177 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/naturalistslibra15jardrich#page/176/mode/2up |title=The Naturalist's Library. Vol. 15 Mammalia |editor1-last=Jardine |editor1-first=W. |location=London |publisher=Chatto and Windus}}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several naturalists described [[zoological specimen]]s from Southern and East Africa and proposed the following subspecies:\n*''Felis leo somaliensis'' <small>(Noack 1891)</small>, based on two lion specimens from [[Somalia]]<ref name=Noack1891>{{cite journal |author=Noack, T. |year=1891 |title=''Felis leo'' |journal=Jahrbuch der Hamburgischen Wissenschaftlichen Anstalten |volume=9 |issue=1 |page=120 |url=}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo massaicus'' <small>([[Oscar Rudolph Neumann|Neumann]] 1900)</small>, based on two lions killed near [[Kibaya]] and the Gurui River in [[Kenya]]<ref name=Neumann>{{cite journal |author=Neumann, O. |year=1900 |title=Die von mir in den Jahren 1892\u201395 in Ost- und Central-Afrika, speciell in den Massai-L\u00e4ndern und den L\u00e4ndern am Victoria Nyansa gesammelten und beobachteten S\u00e4ugethiere |journal=Zoologische Jahrb\u00fccher. Abtheilung f\u00fcr Systematik, Geographie und Biologie der Thiere |volume=13 |issue=VI |pages=529\u2013562 |url=https://archive.org/stream/zoologischejahrb13jena#page/550/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo sabakiensis'' <small>([[Einar L\u00f6nnberg|L\u00f6nnberg]] 1910)</small>, based on two male lions from the environs of [[Mount Kilimanjaro]]<ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1910\">{{cite book |author=L\u00f6nnberg, E. |year=1910 |chapter=Mammals |title=Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Schwedischen Zoologischen Expedition nach dem Kilimandjaro, dem Meru und den umgebenden Massaisteppen Deutsch-Ostafrikas 1905\u20131906. Volume 1 |location=Stockholm |publisher=P. Palmquists Aktiebolag |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/wissenschaftlich01sj#page/n133/mode/2up |pages=1\u221258, Plate 1\u22127 |editor1-last=Sj\u00f6stedt |editor1-first=Y.}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo roosevelti'' <small>([[Edmund Heller|Heller]] 1913)</small>, a lion from the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] presented to [[Theodore Roosevelt]]<ref name=Heller>{{cite journal |author=Heller, E. |year=1913 |title=New races of carnivores and baboons from equatorial Africa and Abyssinia |journal=Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections |volume=61 |issue=19 |pages=1\u201312 |url=https://archive.org/stream/smithsonianmisce611914smit#page/n583/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Felis leo nyanzae'' <small>(Heller 1913)</small>, a lion skin from [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]<ref name=Heller/>\n*''Felis leo bleyenberghi'' <small>(L\u00f6nnberg 1914)</small>, a male lion from the [[Katanga Province]] of [[Belgian Congo]]<ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1914\">{{cite journal |author=L\u00f6nnberg, E. |year=1914 |title=New and rare mammals from Congo |journal=Revue de Zoologie Africaine |issue=3 |pages=273\u2013278 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revuezoologiquea03brux#page/272/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Leo leo hollisteri'' <small>([[Joel Asaph Allen]] 1924)</small>, a male lion from the area of [[Lime Springs, Sotik]] on the eastern shore of [[Lake Victoria]]<ref name=Allen1924>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J. A. |year=1924 |title=Carnivora Collected By The American Museum Congo Expedition |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=47 |pages=73\u2013281 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinamerican47ameruoft#page/223/mode/2up}}</ref>\n*''Leo leo krugeri'' <small>([[Austin Roberts (zoologist)|Austin Roberts]] 1929)</small>, an adult male lion from the [[Sabi Sand Game Reserve]] named in honour of [[Paul Kruger]]<ref name=Roberts1929>{{cite journal |author=Roberts, A. |year=1929 |title=New forms of African mammals |journal=Annals of the Transvaal Museum |volume=21 |issue=13 |pages=82\u2013121 |url=}}</ref>\n*''Leo leo vernayi'' <small>(Roberts 1948)</small>, a male lion from the [[Kalahari]] collected by the [[Arthur Stannard Vernay|Vernay]]-Lang Kalahari Expedition<ref name=Roberts1948>{{cite journal |author=Roberts, A. |year=1948 |title=Descriptions of some new subspecies of mammals |journal=Annals of the Transvaal Museum |volume=21 |issue=1 |pages=63\u201369 |url=}}</ref>\n*''Panthera leo webbensies'' <small>[[:de: Ludwig Zukowsky|Ludwig Zukowsky]] 1964</small>, two lions from [[Somalia]], one in the [[Natural History Museum, Vienna]] that originated in [[Shabeelle River|Webi Shabeelle]], the other kept in a German zoo that had been imported from the hinterland of [[Mogadishu]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Zukowsky, L. |year=1964 |title=Eine neue L\u00f6wenrasse als weiterer Beleg f\u00fcr die Verzwergung der Wirbeltierfauna des afrikanischen Osthorns |journal=Milu, Wissenschaftliche und Kulturelle Mitteilungen aus dem Tierpark Berlin |issue=1 |pages=269\u2013273}}</ref>\n\nDispute over the [[Valid name (zoology)|validity]] of these purported subspecies continued among naturalists and curators of [[natural history museum]]s until the early 21st century.<ref name=Mazak1975/><ref name=Allen1939>{{cite book |last=Allen |first=G. M. |year=1939 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofmuseum83harv#page/242/mode/2up |title=A Checklist of African Mammals |work=Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College |volume=83 |pages=1\u2013763|publisher=Cambridge, Mass. : The Museum }}</ref><ref name=\"Lundholm1952\">{{cite journal |author=Lundholm, B. |year=1952 |title=A skull of a Cape lioness (''Felis leo melanochaitus'' H. Smith |journal=Annals of the Transvaal Museum |issue=32 |pages=21\u201324}}</ref><ref name=Hemmer1974>{{cite journal |author=Hemmer, H. |year=1974 |title=Untersuchungen zur Stammesgeschichte der Pantherkatzen (''Pantherinae'') Teil 3. Zur Artgeschichte des L\u00f6wen ''Panthera (Panthera) leo'' (Linnaeus, 1758) |journal=Ver\u00f6ffentlichungen der Zoologischen Staatssammlung |volume=17| pages=167\u2013280 |url=https://archive.org/stream/verfentlichungen171974zool#page/178/mode/2up}}</ref><ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Carnivora |id=14000228 |page=546 |heading=''Panthera leo''}}</ref>\nIn the 20th century, some authors supported the view of the Cape lion being a distinct subspecies.<ref name=Roberts1929/><ref name=Allen1939/> In 1939, the American zoologist [[Glover Morrill Allen|Allen]] also recognized ''F. l. bleyenberghi'', ''F. l. krugeri'' and ''F. l. vernayi'' as [[Valid name (zoology)|valid]] subspecies in Southern Africa, and ''F. l. hollisteri'', ''F. l. nyanzae'' and ''F. l. massaica'' as valid subspecies in East Africa.<ref name=Allen1939/>\n \n[[Reginald Innes Pocock|Pocock]] subordinated the lion to the [[Genus (biology)|genus]] ''[[Panthera]]'' in 1930, when he wrote about [[Asiatic lion]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Pocock, R. I. |year=1930 |title=The lions of Asia |journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural Historical Society |volume=34 |issue= |pages=638\u2013665 |url=}}</ref> [[Sir John Ellerman, 2nd Baronet|Ellerman]] and [[Terence Morrison-Scott|Morrison-Scott]] recognized only two lion subspecies in the [[Palearctic realm]], namely the African ''P. l. leo'' and the Asiatic ''P. l. persica''.<ref name=\"EllermanMorrisonScott1966\">{{cite book |author1=Ellerman, J. R. |author2=Morrison-Scott, T. C. S. |year=1966 |title=Checklist of Palaearctic and Indian Mammals 1758 to 1946 |location=London |publisher=British Museum (Natural History) |page=319 |chapter=Subgenus ''Leo'' Oken, 1816, (Brehm, 1829) |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/checklistofindia00elle#page/318/mode/2up |edition=Second}}</ref> Various authors recognized between seven and 10 African lion subspecies.<ref name=Hemmer1974/> Others followed the [[Taxonomic classification|classification]] proposed by Ellerman and Morrison-Scott, recognizing two subspecies including one in Africa.<ref name=MeesterSetzer1977>{{cite book |author=Meester, J. |author2=Setzer, H. W. |year=1977 |title=The mammals of Africa. An identification manual |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |url=}}</ref>\n \nIn the 1970s, the scientific name ''P. l. vernayi'' was considered [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonym]]ous with ''P. l. krugeri''.<ref name=Hemmer1974/> In 1975, [[Vratislav Maz\u00e1k]] hypothesized that the Cape lion evolved geographically isolated from other populations by the [[Great Escarpment, Southern Africa|Great Escarpment]].<ref name=Mazak1975/> In the early 21st century, Maz\u00e1k's hypothesis about a geographically isolated evolution of the Cape lion was challenged. Genetic exchanges between populations in the Cape, Kalahari and [[Transvaal Province]] regions and farther east are considered having been possible through a corridor between the Great Escarpment and the [[Indian ocean]].<ref name=Yamaguchi2000>{{cite journal |author=Yamaguchi, N. |year=2000 |url=http://www.tigertouch.org/documents/barbarycape.pdf |title=The Barbary lion and the Cape lion: their phylogenetic places and conservation |journal=African Lion Working Group News |volume=1 |pages=9\u201311}}</ref><ref name=Barnett2006>{{cite journal |author1=Barnett, R. |author2=Yamaguchi, N. |author3=Barnes, I. |author4=Cooper, A. |year=2006 |url=http://abc.zoo.ox.ac.uk/Papers/consgen06_lion.pdf |title=Lost populations and preserving genetic diversity in the lion ''Panthera leo'': Implications for its ex situ conservation |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=507\u2013514 |doi=10.1007/s10592-005-9062-0 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2006-08-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824064412/http://abc.zoo.ox.ac.uk/Papers/consgen06_lion.pdf }}</ref>\n \nIn 2005, the authors of ''[[Mammal Species of the World]]'' recognized ''P. l. bleyenberghi'', ''P. l. krugeri'', ''P. l. vernayi'', ''P. l. massaica'', ''P. l. hollisteri'' and ''P. l. nyanzae'' as valid [[Taxon|taxa]].<ref name=MSW3/> In 2016, [[IUCN Red List]] assessors subsumed all African lion populations to ''P. l. leo''.<ref name=iucn/> Two lion subspecies are now recognised:<ref name=Catsg2017/>\n*''P. l. melanochaita'' is understood as comprising lion populations in the contemporary Southern and East African range countries,\n*[[Panthera leo leo|''P. l. leo'']] comprises lion populations in North, West and Central Africa and Asia.\n \n=== Phylogeny ===\n[[File:Lion subspecies distribution3.png|thumb|Range map including proposed clades and the two subspecies (''P. l. leo'' and ''P. l. melanochaita'') according to genetic research]]\nSince the beginning of the 21st century, several [[phylogenetic]] studies were conducted to aid clarifying the [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic status]] of lion samples kept in museums and collected in the wild. Scientists analysed between 32 and 480 lion samples from up to 22 countries. Results of [[genetic analyses]] indicate that the [[Species (biological)|species]] comprises two main [[evolution]]ary groups, one in Southern and East Africa, and the other in the northern and eastern parts of its historical range.<ref name=\"Barnett_al2006Origin\">{{Cite journal |last1=Barnett |first1=R. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Barnes |first3=I. |last4=Cooper |first4=A. |year=2006 |title=The origin, current diversity and future conservation of the modern lion (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |pmid=16901830 |volume=273 |issue=1598 |pmc=1635511 |pages=2119\u20132125 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2006.3555 |url=http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acad/publications/papers/Barnett%20PRS%20lions.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808182526/http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acad/publications/papers/Barnett%20PRS%20lions.pdf |archive-date=8 August 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Dubach_al2005\">{{Cite journal |last=Dubach |first=J. |last2=Patterson |first2= B. D. |last3=Briggs |first3=M. B. |last4=Venzke |first4=K. |last5=Flamand |first5=J. |last6=Stander |first6=P. |last7=Scheepers |first7=L. |last8=Kays |first8=R. W. |date=2005 |title=Molecular genetic variation across the southern and eastern geographic ranges of the African lion, ''Panthera leo'' |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=15\u201324 |doi=10.1007/s10592-004-7729-6 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226066591}}</ref><ref name=\"Agostinho_al2008\">{{Cite journal |author=Antunes, A. |author2=Troyer, J. L. |author3=Roelke, M. E. |author4=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author5=Packer, C. |author6=Winterbach, C. |author7=Winterbach, H. |author8=Johnson, W. E. |title=The Evolutionary Dynamics of the Lion ''Panthera leo'' revealed by Host and Viral Population Genomics |journal=PLOS Genetics |volume=4 |issue=11 |pages=e1000251 |year=2008 |pmid=18989457 |pmc=2572142 |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1000251}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |authors=Dubach, J. M., Briggs, M. B., White, P. A., Ament, B. A., & Patterson, B. D. |year=2013 |title=Genetic perspectives on \"Lion Conservation Units\" in Eastern and Southern Africa |journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=741\u2212755 |doi=10.1007/s10592-013-0453-3}}</ref> These groups [[Genetic divergence|genetically diverged]] between 50,000 and 200,000 years ago.<ref name=\"O'Brienetal1987\">{{cite journal |author=O\u2019Brien, S. J. |author2=Martenson, J. S. |author3=Packer, C. |author4=Herbst, L. |author5=de Vos, V. |author6=Joslin, P. |author7=Ott-Joslin, J. |author8=Wildt, D. E. |author9=Bush, M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1987 |title=Biochemical genetic variation in geographic isolates of African and Asiatic lions |url=http://www.cbs.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/downloads/Biochemical_Genetic_Variation_in_Geographic_Isolates_of_African_and_Asiatic_Lions.pdf |journal=National Geographic Research |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=114\u2013124 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502101107/http://www.cbs.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/downloads/Biochemical_Genetic_Variation_in_Geographic_Isolates_of_African_and_Asiatic_Lions.pdf |archive-date=2013-05-02}}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2016/> It was assumed that [[tropical rainforest]] and the [[East African Rift]] constituted major barriers between the two groups.<ref name=Barnett2006/><ref name=\"Agostinho_al2008\"/><ref name=\"Mazak2010\">{{cite journal |author=Maz\u00e1k, J. H. |year=2010 |title=Geographical variation and phylogenetics of modern lions based on craniometric data |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=281 |issue=3 |pages=194\u2212209}}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2011>{{Cite journal |last1=Bertola |first1=L. D. |last2=Van Hooft |first2=W. F. |last3=Vrieling |first3=K. |last4=Uit De Weerd |first4=D. R. |last5=York |first5=D. S. |last6=Bauer |first6=H. |last7=Prins |first7=H. H. T. |last8=Funston |first8=P. J. |last9=Udo De Haes |first9=H. A. |last10=Leirs |first10=H. |last11=Van Haeringen |first11=W. A. |last12=Sogbohossou |first12=E. |last13=Tumenta |first13=P. N. |last14=De Iongh |first14=H. H. |title=Genetic diversity, evolutionary history and implications for conservation of the lion (''Panthera leo'') in West and Central Africa |journal=[[Journal of Biogeography]] |volume=38 |issue=7 |pages=1356\u20131367 |year=2011 |url=http://dspace.learningnetworks.org/bitstream/1820/4311/1/2011_Bertola,Hooft,Vrieling,Weerd,York,Bauer,Prins,Haes,Iongh_GeneticDiversityEvolutionaryHistoryAndImplicationsForConservationOfTheLionInWestAndCentralAfrica.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2699.2011.02500.x |access-date=2018-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608070014/http://dspace.learningnetworks.org/bitstream/1820/4311/1/2011_Bertola,Hooft,Vrieling,Weerd,York,Bauer,Prins,Haes,Iongh_GeneticDiversityEvolutionaryHistoryAndImplicationsForConservationOfTheLionInWestAndCentralAfrica.pdf |archive-date=2019-06-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2015>{{cite journal |authors=Bertola, L. D., Tensen, L., Van Hooft, P., White, P. A., Driscoll, C. A., Henschel, P., Caragiulo, A., Dias-Freedman, I., Sogbohossou, E. A., Tumenta, P. N. and Jirmo, T. H. |year=2015 |title=Autosomal and mtDNA markers affirm the distinctiveness of lions in West and Central Africa |journal=PLOS One |volume=10 |issue=10 |page=e0137975 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0137975|pmid=26466139 |pmc=4605676 |bibcode=2015PLoSO..1037975B }}</ref><ref name=Bertola_al2016>{{cite journal |author=Bertola, L. D. |author2=Jongbloed, H. |author3=Van Der Gaag, K. J. |author4=De Knijff, P. |author5=Yamaguchi, N. |author6=Hooghiemstra, H. |author7=Bauer, H. |author8=Henschel, P. |author9=White, P. A. |author10=Driscoll, C. A. |author11=Tende, T. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2016 |title=Phylogeographic patterns in Africa and High Resolution Delineation of genetic clades in the Lion (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Scientific Reports |volume=6 |page=30807 |doi=10.1038/srep30807|pmid=27488946 |pmc=4973251 |bibcode=2016NatSR...630807B}}</ref>\n\nLion samples from Gabon's [[Bat\u00e9k\u00e9 Plateau National Park]] and [[Odzala-Kokoua National Park]] in Republic of the Congo were found to be genetically closely related to lion samples from Namibia and Botswana.<ref name=Barnett_al2018/>\n\n=== Overlap between subspecies ===\n[[File:Annual report - New York Zoological Society (1914) (18433145331).jpg|thumb|Lion from Ethiopia at [[Bronx Zoo]]]]\nAmong six samples of captive lions from Ethiopia, five clustered with samples from East Africa, but one with samples from the [[Sahel]].<ref name=Bertola_al2011/> For a subsequent [[phylogeographic]] study, eight wild lion samples from the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] were included in the [[DNA sequencing]] analysis using 194 lion samples from 22 countries. Four of these samples [[Cluster (statistics)|cluster]]ed with samples from Central Africa, and four with samples from East Africa, indicating that the [[Great Rift Valley, Ethiopia]] was not a complete barrier to [[gene flow]]. Southeastern Ethiopia is therefore considered a [[genetic admixture]] zone between Central and East African lions.<ref name=Bertola_al2016/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n|image1=Lion_cubs,_Zimbabwe_(5213422527).jpg |caption1=Lion cubs in Zimbabwe\n|image2=Lions on rock-2.jpg |caption2=Adult male lions in [[Serengeti National Park]]\n|image3=Male panthera leo Kenya 07 (cropped).jpg |caption3=Male lion in [[Narok County]]\n}}\nThe lion's fur varies in colour from light buff to dark brown. It has rounded ears and a black tail tuft.<ref name=Guggisberg1975>{{cite book |last=Guggisberg |first=C. A. W. |chapter=Lion ''Panthera leo'' (Linnaeus, 1758) |title=Wild Cats of the World |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00gugg |chapter-url-access=registration |year=1975 |publisher=Taplinger Publishing |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8008-8324-9 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00gugg/page/138 138\u2013179]}}</ref>\n\n=== Manes ===\nIn the 19th and 20th centuries, lion [[type specimen]]s were described on the basis of their mane size and colour. Mane colour varies from sandy, tawny, isabelline, light reddish yellow to dark brown and black.<ref name=Smith1842/><ref name=Heller/><ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1914\"/><ref name=\"Guggisberg1963\">{{cite book |author=Guggisberg, Charles Albert Walter |title=Simba: The Life of the Lion |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4eTaAAAAMAAJ |year=1963 |publisher=Chilton Books |location=Philadelphia, PA |page= |asin=B000OKBJQ0}}</ref><ref name=Smithers1971>{{cite book |last=Smithers |first=R. H. N. |year=1971 |title=The Mammals of Botswana |publisher=University of Pretoria |location=Pretoria |chapter=Panthera leo |pages=116\u2212119}}</ref> Mane length varies from short to extending to knee joints and under the belly.<ref name=Hemmer1974/>\nLions without a mane were observed in the Tsavo area.<ref name=\"Borzo2002\"/>\n\nMane development is related to age: older males have more extensive manes than younger ones; manes continue to grow up to the age of four to five years, long after lions become [[sexually mature]]. Males living in the highlands above altitudes of {{convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}} develop heavier manes than lions in the more humid and warmer lowlands of eastern and northern Kenya. The latter have thinner manes, or are even [[maneless lion|maneless]].<ref name=\"Gnoskeetal2006\">{{cite journal |author1=Gnoske, T. P. |author2=Celesia, G. G. |author3=Kerbis Peterhans, J. C. |year=2006 |title=Dissociation between mane development and sexual maturity in lions (''Panthera leo''): solution to the Tsavo riddle? |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=270 |issue=4 |pages=551\u2013560 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00200.x |bibcode=2010JZoo..281..263G}}</ref> Hence, lion manes reflect ambient temperature. Mane colour is also influenced by nutrition and [[testosterone]]. Its length is an indicator for age and fighting ability of the lion.<ref name=\"WestPacker2002\">{{Cite journal |author1=West, P. M. |author2=Packer, C. |date=2002 |title=Sexual Selection, Temperature, and the Lion's Mane |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=297 |issue=5585 |pages=1339\u20131943 |doi=10.1126/science.1073257 |pmid=12193785 |bibcode=2002Sci...297.1339W}}</ref>\n\n=== Size and weight ===\nAverage head-to-body length of male lions is {{convert|2.47|-|2.84|m|in|abbr=on}} with an average weight of {{convert|187|-|263|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in Southern Africa and {{convert|174.9-255|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in East Africa. Females average {{convert|124.2|-|149.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in Southern Africa and {{convert|119.5-145.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in East Africa.<ref name=Smuts_etal_1980>{{cite journal |author1=Smuts, G. L. |author2=Robinson, G. A. |author3=Whyte, I. J. |title=Comparative growth of wild male and female lions (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Journal of Zoology |year=1980 |volume=190 |issue=3 |pages=365\u2013373 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1980.tb01433.x |bibcode=2010JZoo..281..263G}}</ref>\nMales in Kruger National Park weighed {{convert|200.01|and|266.55|kg|lb|abbr=on}} on average, whereas females weighed {{convert|143.52|and|118.37|kg|lb|abbr=on}} on average, though there was an outbreak of [[tuberculosis]] in the park at the time.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keet |first1=D. F. |last2=Kriek |first2=N. P. J. |last3=Mills |first3=M. G. L. |title=The epidemiology of tuberculosis in free-ranging lions in the Kruger National Park |publisher=[[South African National Parks]] |year=1999 |access-date=2019-08-13 |url=https://www.sanparks.org/parks/kruger/conservation/scientific/projects/Project_Reports_PDF/73.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe largest known lion measured {{convert|3.35|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Guggisberg1975\"/> An exceptionally heavy male lion near [[Mount Kenya National Park|Mount Kenya]] weighed {{convert|322|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"NowellJackson1996\">{{cite book |author1=Nowell, K. |author2=Jackson, P. |chapter=African lion |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |chapterurl=http://carnivoractionplans1.free.fr/wildcats.pdf |year=1996 |publisher=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |location=Gland, Switzerland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |pages=17\u201321}}</ref> The longest wild lion reportedly was a male shot near [[Mucusso National Park]] in southern Angola in 1973. In 1936, a [[man-eating]] lion shot in 1936 in eastern Transvaal weighed about {{convert|343|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and was considered to have been one of heaviest wild lions. <ref name=Wood1983>{{cite book |last=Wood |first=G. L. |year=1982 |title=The Guinness Book of Animal Facts and Feats |location=Enfield, Middlesex |edition=Third |publisher=Guinness Superlatives Ltd. |isbn=978-0-85112-235-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessbookofan00wood}}</ref> In 1963, two lions in Tanzania weighed {{convert|730.5|lbs|kg|order=flip|abbr=on}} and {{convert|380|kg|lbs|order=flip|abbr=on}} after killing [[livestock]].<ref name=\"UPA1963\">{{cite book |work=University Press of Africa, with contributions from the Kenya National Chamber of Commerce & Industry |title=East African Business Digest |url=https://books.google.com/?id=i_JPAQAAIAAJ |year=1963 |access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== White lion ===\n{{Main|White lion}}\n[[File:Kruger Cub.jpg|thumb|A cub in Kruger National Park]]\nWhite lions have occasionally been encountered in and around South Africa's [[Kruger National Park]] and the adjacent [[Timbavati Private Game Reserve]]. Their whitish fur is a rare [[Polymorphism (biology)|morph]] caused by a double [[Dominance (genetics)|recessive]] [[allele]]. It has normal pigmentation in eyes and skin. They were removed from the wild in the 1970s, thus decreasing the white lion [[gene pool]]. Nevertheless, 17 births have been recorded in five different prides between 2007 and 2015.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Turner |first1=J. A. |last2=Vasicek |first2=C. A. |last3=Somers |first3=M. J. |year=2015 |title=Effects of a colour variant on hunting ability: the white lion in South Africa |journal=Open Science Repository Biology |page=e45011830}}</ref> White lions were selected for breeding in [[captivity (animal)|captivity]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=McBride |first=C. |title=The White Lions of Timbavati |year=1977 |publisher=E. Stanton |location=[[Johannesburg]] |isbn=978-0-949997-32-6}}</ref> They have been bred in South African camps for use as trophies to be killed during [[canned hunt]]s.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Tucker |first=L. |title=Mystery of the White Lions\u2014Children of the Sun God |year=2003 |publisher=Npenvu Press |location=[[Mapumalanga]] |isbn=978-0-620-31409-1}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |image1=Lion_cubs_Serengeti.jpg |image2=7 lions.jpg |image3=Lionesses with cubs, Selous Game Reserve (28) (28436353633).jpg |footer=The Serengeti and Maasai Mara National Parks and Selous Game Reserve are lion strongholds in East Africa with stable lion populations<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>}}\nIn East and Southern Africa, lion populations declined in:\n*[[Somalia]] since the early 20th century.<ref name=\"FunaioliSimonetta1966\">{{cite journal |author=Funaioli, U. and Simonetta, A. M. |year=1966 |title=The Mammalian Fauna of the Somali Republic: Status and Conservation Problems |journal=Monitore Zoologico Italiano, Supplemento |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=285\u2013347 |doi=10.1080/03749444.1966.10736746}}</ref> Intensive [[poaching]] since the 1980s and civil unrest posed a threat to lion persistence.<ref name=Chardonnet2002>{{cite book |author=Chardonnet, P. |year=2002 |title=Conservation of the African Lion : Contribution to a Status Survey |location=Paris |publisher=International Foundation for the Conservation of Wildlife, France & Conservation Force, USA |chapter=Chapter II: Population Survey |pages=21\u2013101 |chapterurl=http://conservationforce.org/pdf/conservationoftheafricanlion.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110184540/http://conservationforce.org/pdf/conservationoftheafricanlion.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Fagotto1985\">{{cite journal |author=Fagotto, F. |year=1985 |title=Larger animals of Somalia in 1984 |journal=Environmental Conservation |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=260\u2212264|doi=10.1017/S0376892900016015}}</ref>\n*[[Uganda]] to near extinction in the 20th century.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Treves, A. |author2=Naughton-Treves, L. |year=1999 |title=Risk and opportunity for humans coexisting with large carnivores |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=275\u2212282 |doi=10.1006/jhev.1998.0268 |pmid=10074384|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/68f322bacfaa9cbbb282b23865499b6bd99a9301 }}</ref> In 2010, the lion population in Uganda was estimated at 408 \u00b1 46 individuals in three protected areas including Queen Elizabeth, Murchison Falls and Kidepo Valley National Parks. Other protected areas in the country probably host less than 10 lions.<ref name=Omoya_al2014>{{cite journal |author1=Omoya, E. O. |author2=Mudumba, T. |author3=Buckland, S. T. |author4=Mulondo, P. |author5=Plumptre, A. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2014 |title=Estimating population sizes of lions ''Panthera leo'' and spotted hyaenas ''Crocuta crocuta'' in Uganda's savannah parks, using lure count methods |journal=Oryx |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=394\u2013401 |doi=10.1017/S0030605313000112 |url=https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/10023/6885/omoya2014oryx394.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref> Lions in [[Queen Elizabeth National Park]] form a contiguous population with lions in [[Virunga National Park]].<ref name=Treves_al2009>{{cite journal |author1=Treves, A. |author2=Plumptre, A. J. |author3=Hunter, L. T. B. |author4=Ziwa, J. |year=2009 |title=Identifying a potential lion ''Panthera leo'' stronghold in Queen Elizabeth National Park, Uganda, and Parc National des Virunga, Democratic Republic of Congo |journal=Oryx |volume=43 |pages=60\u221266 |doi=10.1017/S003060530700124X}}</ref>\n*[[Kenya]] in the 1990s due to poisoning of lions and poaching of lion prey species.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/> At least 108 lions were killed between 2001 and 2006 in the [[Amboseli National Park|Amboseli]]\u2212[[Tsavo West National Park|Tsavo West]]\u2212[[Tsavo East National Park]] network.<ref name=Frank_al2006>{{cite book |author1=Frank, L.  |author2=Maclennan, S. |author3=Hazzah, L. |author4=Hill, T. |author5=Bonham, R. |year=2006 |title=Lion Killing in the Amboseli-Tsavo Ecosystem, 2001\u20132006, and its Implications for Kenya's Lion Population |publisher=Living with Lions |location=Nairobi |url=http://www.livingwithlions.org/AnnualReports/2006-Lion-killing-in-Amboseli-Tsavo-ecosystem.pdf}}</ref> As of 2006, there were an estimated 675 lions in the Tsavo national parks, out of the 2,000 total in Kenya.<ref name=Frank_al2006/> Between 2004 and 2013, lion guardians around Amboseli National Park identified 65 lions in an area of {{convert|3684|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dolrenry, S. |author2=Hazzah, L. |author3=Frank, L. G. |year=2016 |title=Conservation and monitoring of a persecuted African lion population by Maasai warriors |volume=30 |journal=Conservation Biology |issue=3 |pages=467\u2212475 |doi= 10.1111/cobi.12703|pmid=27111059}}</ref> Lion populations in Kenya and Tanzania are fragmented over 17 patches ranging in size from {{convert|86|to|127515|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dolrenry, S. |author2=Stenglein, J. |author3=Hazzah, L. |author4=Lutz, R. S. |author5=Frank, L. |year=2014 |title=A metapopulation approach to African lion (''Panthera leo'') conservation |journal= PLOS One |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=e88081 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0088081 |pmid=24505385 |pmc=3914926 |bibcode=2014PLoSO...988081D}}</ref>\n*[[Rwanda]] and [[Tanzania]] due to killing of lions during the [[Rwandan Civil War]] and ensuing [[Great Lakes refugee crisis|refugee crisis]] in the 1990s.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/> A small population was present in Rwanda's [[Akagera National Park]], estimated at 35 individuals at most in 2004.<ref name=Bauer_vanderMerwe>{{Cite journal |last1=Bauer |first1=H. |last2=Van Der Merwe |first2=S. |doi=10.1017/S0030605304000055 |title=Inventory of free-ranging lions ''Panthera leo'' in Africa |journal=Oryx |volume=38 |year=2004 |issue=1 |pages=26\u201331}}</ref> Lions were reintroduced to this national park in 2015.<ref>{{cite thesis |author=Bantlin, D. A. |year=2017 |title=Movements of Reintroduced Lions in Akagera National Park, Rwanda, in Relation to Prey Abundance |type=Doctoral dissertation |publisher=University of Wisconsin\u2212Madison |location=Madison}}</ref>\n*[[Malawi]] and [[Zambia]] due to illegal hunting of prey species in protected areas.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/>\n*[[Botswana]] due to intensive hunting and conversion of natural habitats for settlements since the early 19th century.<ref name=Smithers1971/> In Northern Tuli Game Reserve, 19 lions died between 2005 and 2011 due to poaching, trophy hunting and [[Trapping#Snares|snaring]].<ref name=Snyman2015>{{cite journal |author1=Snyman, A.  |author2=Jackson, C. R. |author3=Funston, P. J. |year=2015 |title=The effect of alternative forms of hunting on the social organization of two small populations of lions ''Panthera leo'' in Southern Africa |volume=49 |journal=Oryx |issue=4 |pages=604\u2212610 |doi=10.1017/S0030605313001336}}</ref>\n*[[Namibia]] due to massive killing of lions by farmers since at least the 1970s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Stander, P. E. |year=1990 |title=A suggested management strategy for stock-raiding lions in Namibia |journal=South African Journal of Wildlife Research |volume=20 |issue=2|pages=37\u221243}}</ref> In 2010, the small and isolated lion population in the [[Kalahari]] was estimated at 683 to 1,397 individuals in three protected areas, the [[Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park]], the [[Kalahari Gemsbok National Park|Kalahari Gemsbok]] and [[Gemsbok National Park]]s.<ref name=Ferreira_al2013>{{cite journal |author1=Ferreira, S. M. |author2=Govender, D. |author3=Herbst, M. |year=2013 |title=Conservation implications of Kalahari lion population dynamics |journal=African Journal of Ecology |volume=51 |issue=2 |pages=176\u2013179|doi=10.1111/aje.12003}}</ref>\n*[[South Africa]] since the early 19th century in the [[Natal Province|Natal]] and [[Cape Province]]s south of the [[Orange River]], where the Cape lion population was eradicated by 1860.<ref name=Mazak1975/> A few decades later, lions in the [[Highveld]] north of the Orange River were also eradicated.<ref name=\"Guggisberg1975\"/> In [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]], lions occurred historically in the Highveld as well, but were restricted to eastern Transvaal's [[Bushveld]] by the 1970s.<ref>{{cite book |author=Rautenbach, I. L. |year=1978 |title=The Mammals of the Transvaal |publisher=University of Natal |location=[[Pietermaritzburg]] |chapter=''Panthera leo'' (Linnaeus, 1758) |pages=471\u2212475}}</ref> Between 2000 and 2004, 34 lions were reintroduced to eight protected areas in the [[Eastern Cape Province]], including [[Addo Elephant National Park]].<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Hayward, M. W., Adendorff, J., O\u2019Brien, J., Sholto-Douglas, A., Bissett, C., Moolman, L. C., Bean, P., Fogarty, A., Howarth, D., Slater, R. and Kerley, G. I. |year=2007 |title=Practical considerations for the reintroduction of large, terrestrial, mammalian predators based on reintroductions to South Africa's Eastern Cape Province |volume=1 |journal=The Open Conservation Biology Journal |issue=1 |pages=1\u221211 |doi=10.2174/1874839200701010001 |url=http://benthamopen.com/contents/pdf/TOCONSBJ/TOCONSBJ-1-1.pdf}}</ref> In [[Venetia Limpopo Nature Reserve]], 18 lions were trophy hunted and 11 [[euthanized]] between 2005 and 2011.<ref name=Snyman2015/>\n\nContemporary lion distribution and habitat quality in East and Southern Africa was assessed in 2005, and Lion Conservation Units (LCU) mapped.<ref name=csg2006/> Between 2002 and 2012, educated guesses for size of populations in these LCUs ranged from 33,967 to 32,000 individuals.<ref name=Chardonnet2002/><ref name=Riggioetal2013>{{cite journal |author1=Riggio, J. |author2=Jacobson, A. |author3=Dollar, L. |author4=Bauer, H. |author5=Becker, M. |author6=Dickman, A. |author7=Funston, P. |author8=Groom, R. |author9=Henschel, P. |author10=De Iongh, H. |author11=Lichtenfeld, L. |year=2013 |title=The size of savannah Africa: a lion's (''Panthera leo'') view |journal=Biodiversity and Conservation |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201335 |doi=10.1007/s10531-012-0381-4}}</ref>\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- valign=bottom\n! Range countries !! Lion Conservation Units !! Area in km<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|Democratic Republic of Congo ||[[Massif D'itombwe]], [[Luama River|Luama]] ||8,441<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Democratic Republic of Congo, Uganda ||Queen Elizabeth\u2212Virunga National Parks ||5,583<ref name=Treves_al2009/>\n|-\n|Uganda ||[[Toro-Semliki Wildlife Reserve|Toro\u2212Semulik]], [[Lake Mburo National Park|Lake Mburo]], [[Murchison Falls National Park|Murchison Falls]] ||4,800<ref>{{cite book |author1=Mudumba, T. |author2=Mulondo, P. |author3=Okot, E. |author4=Nsubuga, M. |author5=Plumptre, A. |year=2009 |title= National Census of Lions and Hyaenas in Uganda. Strategic Action Plan for Large Carnivore Conservation in Uganda |location=Kampala |publisher=[[Uganda Wildlife Authority]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|Somalia ||[[Lower Shabelle|Arboweerow\u2212Alafuuto]] ||24,527<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Somalia, Kenya ||[[Lag Badana National Park|Bushbush]]\u2212[[Arawale National Reserve|Arawale]]||22,540<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Kenya ||[[Laikipia County|Laikipia]]\u2212[[Samburu National Reserve|Samburu]], [[Meru National Park|Meru]] and [[Nairobi National Park]]s ||43,706<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Kenya, Tanzania ||[[Serengeti National Park|Serengeti]]\u2212[[Maasai Mara National Reserve|Mara]] and [[Tsavo East National Park|Tsavo]]\u2212[[Mkomazi National Park|Mkomazi]] ||75,068<ref name=Mesochina2010>{{cite book |author1=M\u00e9sochina, P. |author2=Mbangwa, O. |author3=Chardonnet, P. |author4=Mosha, R. |author5=Mtui, B. |author6=Drouet, N. |author7=Kissui, B. |year=2010 |title=Conservation status of the lion (''Panthera leo'' Linnaeus, 1758) in Tanzania |location=[[Paris]] |publisher=SCI Foundation, MNRT-WD, TAWISA & IGF Foundation}}</ref>\n|-\n|Tanzania ||Dar-[[Biharamulo Game Reserve|Biharamulo]], [[Ruaha National Park|Ruaha]]\u2212[[Rungwa Game Reserve|Rungwa]], [[Mpanga-Kipengere Game Reserve|Mpanga-Kipengere]], [[Tarangire National Park|Tarangire]], [[Wami River|Wami]] Mbiki\u2212[[Saadani National Park|Saadani]], [[Selous Game Reserve|Selous]] ||384,489<ref name=Mesochina2010/>\n|-\n|Tanzania, Mozambique ||[[Niassa Reserve|Niassa]] ||177,559<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009>{{cite book |author1=Chardonnet, P. |author2=M\u00e9sochina, P. |author3=Bento, C. |author4=Conjo, D. |author5=Begg, C. l. |year=2009 |title=Conservation status of the lion (''Panthera leo'' Linnaeus, 1758) in Mozambique |location=Maputo, Mozambique |publisher=Fondation IGF, Campfire Association, SCI Foundation, The Ratel Trust, Direc\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional de Terras e Florestas |url=https://agritrop.cirad.fr/550720/1/document_550720.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n|Mozambique ||[[Cahora Bassa]], [[Gil\u00e9 District|Gil\u00e9]], [[Gorongosa National Park|Gorongosa]]\u2212[[Marromeu District|Marromeu]] ||82,715<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009/>\n|-\n|Mozambique, Zambia ||[[Zambezi#Middle Zambezi|Middle Zambezi]] ||64,672<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009/>\n|-\n|Mozambique, South Africa ||[[Great Limpopo Transfrontier Park]] ||150,347<ref name=Chardonnet_al2009/>\n|-\n|Zambia ||[[Liuwa Plain National Park|Liuwa Plains]], [[Sioma Ngwezi National Park|Sioma Ngwezi]], [[Kafue National Park|Kafue Sumbu Complex]] ||72,569<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Zambia, Malawi ||[[North Luangwa National Park|North]]\u2212[[South Luangwa National Park|South Luangwa]]||72,992<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Malawi ||[[Kasungu National Park|Kasungu]], [[Nkhotakota Wildlife Reserve|Nkhotakota]] ||4,187<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Zimbabwe ||[[Mapungubwe National Park|Mapungubwe]], [[Bubye River|Bubye]] ||10,033<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Botswana, Zimbabwe ||[[Okavango Delta|Okavango]]\u2212[[Hwange National Park|Hwange]] ||99,552<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Botswana ||[[Moremi Game Reserve|Xaixai]] ||12,484<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Botswana, South Africa ||[[Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park|Kgalagadi]] ||163,329<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n|-\n|Angola ||[[Qui\u00e7ama National Park|Kissama]]\u2212Mumbondo, [[Benguela Province|Bocoio]]\u2212[[Camacuio]], [[Alto Zambeze]] ||393,760<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Angola, Namibia ||[[Etosha National Park|Etosha]]\u2212[[Kunene Region|Kunene]] ||123,800<ref name=csg2006/>\n|-\n|Namibia ||[[Khaudum National Park|Khaudum]]\u2212[[Caprivi Game Park|Caprivi]] ||92,372<ref name=csg2006/>\n|}\n \nThe LCUs Ruaha\u2212Rungwa, Serengeti\u2212Mara, Tsavo\u2212Mkomazi and Selous in East Africa, as well as Luangwa, Kgalagadi, Okavango\u2212Hwange, Mid\u2212Zambezi, Niassa and Greater Limpopo in Southern Africa are currently considered lion strongholds. These LCUs host more than 500 individuals each, and the population trend is stable there as of 2012.<ref name=Riggioetal2013/>\n\n== Behaviour and ecology ==\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n|image1=FrontLines_Environment_Photo_Contest_Winner_-7_(5809039672).jpg |caption1=Tree-climbing lion in Murchison Falls National Park\n|image2=Zimbabwe 4888bb.jpg |caption2=Lion pride at the [[Zambezi]] River\n|image3=Mating Lion, Etosha National Park, Namibia.jpg |caption3=Lions mating in Etosha National Park\n|image4=690V3740 - Flickr - Lip Kee.jpg |caption4=A lioness with her cub in Botswana}}\nIn [[Serengeti National Park]], monitoring of lion prides started in 1966.<ref name=Schaller72>{{Cite book |last=Schaller |first=G. B. |authorlink=George Schaller |year=1972 |title=The Serengeti lion: A study of predator\u2013prey relations |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |isbn=978-0-226-73639-6}}</ref>\nBetween 1966 and 1972, two observed lion prides comprised between seven and 10 females each. Females had litters once in 23 months on average.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Bertram, B.C.R. |year=1973 |title=Lion population regulation |journal=East African Wildlife Journal |volume=11 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=215\u2212225|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1973.tb00088.x }}</ref>\nLitters contained two to three cubs. Of 87 cubs born until 1970, only 12 reached the age of two years. Cubs died due to starvation in months when large prey was not available, or following take-over of the prides by new males.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Bertram, B. |year=1975 |title=Social factors influencing reproduction in wild lions |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=177 |issue=4 |pages=463\u2013482|doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1975.tb02246.x }}</ref> Male lions in coalitions are closely related.<ref name=Bygott1979>{{cite journal |authors=Bygott, J. D., Bertram, B. C. R., and Hanby, J. P. |year=1979 |title=Male lions in large coalitions gain reproductive advantages |journal=Nature |volume=282 |issue=5741 |pages=839\u2013841|bibcode=1979Natur.282..839B |doi=10.1038/282839a0 }}</ref>\nBetween 1974 and 2012, 471 coalitions comprising 796 male lions entered a study area of {{convert|2000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. Of these, 35 coalitions included male lions that were born in the area but had left and returned after about two years of absence. Nomadic coalitions became resident at between 3.5 and 7.3 years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Borrego, N. |author2=Ozgul, A. |author3=Slotow, R. |author4=Packer, C. |year=2018 |title=Lion population dynamics: do nomadic males matter? |journal=Behavioral Ecology |volume=29 |issue=3 |doi=10.1093/beheco/ary018 |pages=660\u2013666 |url=}}</ref>\n\nThe lion population of Selous Game Reserve has been surveyed since 1996. Lion prides avoided [[acacia]] woodlands and preferred habitats near water courses with short grasses, where also prey species gathered. Two or more prides shared home ranges.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Spong, G. |year=2002 |title=Space use in lions, ''Panthera leo'', in the Selous Game Reserve: social and ecological factors |journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |volume=52 |issue=4 |pages=303\u2013307 |doi=10.1007/s00265-002-0515-x}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Kavango\u2013Zambezi Transfrontier Conservation Area]], lions have been monitored since 1999. In 2003, 50 lions were [[Radio telemetry|radio-collared]] in [[Hwange National Park]] and tracked until 2012. Results show that adult male and female lions preferred grassland and [[shrubland]] habitat, but avoided woodlands and areas with high human density. By contrast, subadult [[biological dispersal|dispersing]] male lions avoided grasslands and shrublands, but moved in human-dominated areas to a larger extent. Hence, dispersing lions are more vulnerable to coming into [[Human\u2013wildlife conflict|conflict]] with humans than adult lions.<ref name=Elliot_al2014>{{cite journal |author1=Elliot, N. B. |author2=Cushman, S. A. |author3=Macdonald, D. W. |author4=Loveridge, A. J. |year=2014 |title=The devil is in the dispersers: predictions of landscape connectivity change with demography |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=1169\u20131178 |doi=10.1111/1365-2664.12282}}</ref>\nIn the semi-arid savanna of Zimbabwe's Hwange National Park, 19 lions were radio-collared and tracked between 2002 and 2007. Both female and male lions moved foremost within {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} of waterholes in all seasons.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Valeix, M., Loveridge, A. J., Davidson, Z., Madzikanda, H., Fritz, H. and Macdonald, D. W. |year=2010 |title=How key habitat features influence large terrestrial carnivore movements: waterholes and African lions in a semi-arid savanna of north-western Zimbabwe |volume=25 |journal=Landscape Ecology |issue=3 |pages=337\u2013351 |doi=10.1007/s10980-009-9425-x}}</ref>\n\nLions living near ranches in the vicinity of Tsavo East National Park consisted of three prides, two pairs and a single lion in 2002.<ref name=Patterson_al2004>{{cite journal |author=Patterson, B. D., Kasiki, S. M., Selempo, E. and Kays, R. W. |year=2004 |title=Livestock predation by lions (''Panthera leo'') and other carnivores on ranches neighboring Tsavo National Parks, Kenya |volume=119 |journal=Biological Conservation |issue=4 |pages=507\u2212516 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2004.01.013 |citeseerx=10.1.1.884.8117 }}</ref>\n\n=== Hunting and diet ===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n|image1=Lions hunting Africa.jpg |caption1=Lionesses hunting a Cape buffalo in the Okavango Delta\n|image2=Tinga 2012 05 20 0951 (7407622938).jpg |caption2=Lions feeding on a giraffe in Kruger National Park\n}}\nLions usually [[Cooperative hunting|hunt in groups]] and [[prey]] foremost on [[ungulate]]s such as [[gemsbok]] (''Oryx gazella''), [[Cape buffalo]] (''Syncerus caffer''), [[blue wildebeest]] (''Connochaetes taurinus''), [[giraffe]] (''Giraffa camelopardalis''), [[common eland]] (''Tragelaphus oryx''), [[greater kudu]] (''T. strepsiceros''), [[nyala]] (''T. angasii''), [[roan antelope]] (''Hippotragus equinus''), [[sable antelope]] (''H. niger''), [[plains zebra]] (''Equus quagga''), [[bushpig]] (''Potamochoerus larvatus''), [[common warthog]] (''Phacochoerus africanus''), [[hartebeest]] (''Alcephalus buselaphus''), [[common tsessebe]] (''Damaliscus lunatus''), [[waterbuck]] (''Kobus ellipsiprymnus''), [[kob]] (''K. kob'') and [[Thomson's gazelle]] (''Eudorcas thomsonii''). Their prey is usually in the range of {{convert|190|-|550|kg|lb|abbr=in}}.<ref name=Hayward2005>{{Cite journal |last1=Hayward |first1=M. W. |last2=Kerley |first2=G. I. H. |year=2005 |title=Prey preferences of the lion (''Panthera leo'') |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=267 |issue=3 |pages=309\u2013322 |doi=10.1017/S0952836905007508 |url=http://www.zbs.bialowieza.pl/g2/pdf/1595.pdf |bibcode=2010JZoo..281..263G |citeseerx=10.1.1.611.8271}}</ref> In the Serengeti National Park, lions were observed to also [[Scavenger|scavenge]] on [[carrion]] of animals that were killed by other predators, or died from natural causes. They kept a constant lookout for circling vultures, apparently being aware that vultures indicate a dead animal.<ref name=Schaller72/>\nFaeces of lions collected near waterholes in Hwange National Park also contained remains of climbing mice (''[[Dendromus]]'') and common mice (''[[Mus (genus)|Mus]]'').<ref>{{cite journal |author=Davidson, Z., Valeix, M., Van Kesteren, F., Loveridge, A.J., Hunt, J.E., Murindagomo, F. and Macdonald, D.W. |year=2013 |title=Seasonal diet and prey preference of the African lion in a waterhole-driven semi-arid savanna |volume=8 |journal=PLOS One |issue=2 |pages=e55182 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0055182.g001|pmid=23405121 |pmc=3566210 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...855182D }}</ref>\n \nIn Botswana's [[Chobe National Park]], lions also prey on [[African bush elephant]]s (''Loxodonta africana''). They successfully attacked 74 elephants between 1993 and 1996, of which 26 were older than nine years, and one bull over 15 years old.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Joubert |first1=D. |year=2006 |title=Hunting behaviour of lions (''Panthera leo'') on elephants (''Loxodonta africana'') in the Chobe National Park, Botswana |journal= African Journal of Ecology |volume=44 |issue=2 |pages=279\u2013281 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.2006.00626.x}}</ref> In October 2005, a pride of up to 30 lions killed eight African bush elephants that were between four and eleven years old.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Power |first1=R. J. |last2=Compion |first2=R. X. S. |title=Lion predation on elephants in the Savuti, Chobe National Park, Botswana |journal=African Zoology |volume=44 |issue=1 |pages=36\u201344 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232693088 |doi=10.3377/004.044.0104 |year=2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Attacks on humans ===\nSeveral cases of lion attacking people have been documented:\n*In the 1890s, two [[Tsavo Man-Eaters]] attacked workers during the building of the [[Uganda Railway]]. Their [[skull]]s and [[skin]]s are part of the zoological collection of the [[Field Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kerbis Peterhans, J. C. and Gnoske, T. P. |year=2001 |title=The Science of 'Man-Eating*' Among Lions ''Panthera leo'' With a Reconstruction of the Natural History of the 'Man-Eaters of Tsavo' |journal=Journal of East African Natural History |issue=1 |pages=1\u201340 |doi=10.2982/0012-8317(2001)90[1:TSOMAL]2.0.CO;2 |volume=90}}</ref> The total number of people killed is unclear, but allegedly 135 people fell victim to these lions in less than a year before [[John Henry Patterson (author)|Colonel Patterson]] killed them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Patterson |first=J. H. |author-link=John Henry Patterson (author) |year=1907 |url=https://archive.org/details/maneatersoftsavo00pattiala |title=The man-eaters of Tsavo and other East African adventures |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Macmillan and Co.]]}}</ref>\n* The Njombe lions were a lion pride in [[Njombe]] in former [[Tanganyika]], which are thought to have preyed on 1,500 to 2,000 people. They were killed by [[George Gilman Rushby]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Rushby |first=G. G. |title=No More the Tusker |year=1965 |publisher=W. H. Allen |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wneBAAAAIAAJ}}</ref>\n*Between 1990 and 2004, lions killed more than 560 people in Tanzania, mostly during harvest season in crop fields and in areas where natural prey is scarce.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Packer, C., Ikanda, D., Kissui, B. and Kushnir, H. |year=2005 |title=Lion attacks on humans in Tanzania |volume=436 |issue=7052 |journal=Nature |pages=927\u2212928 |doi=10.1038/436791a |pmid=16094358 |bibcode=2005Natur.436..791S |url=https://www.cbs.umn.edu/sites/cbs.umn.edu/files/public/downloads/Lion_attacks_on_humans_in_Tanzania.pdf}}</ref>\n* In February 2018, lions killed a suspected poacher near Kruger National Park.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=The [[BBC]] |title=South African lions eat 'poacher', leaving just his head |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43035474 |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Haden, A. |title=Suspected poacher mauled to death by lions close to Kruger National Park |publisher=The South African |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/suspected-poacher-killed-by-lions/ |date=2018 |access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* In February 2018, [[Kevin Richardson (zookeeper)|Kevin Richardson]] took three lions for a walk at Dinokeng Game Reserve in South Africa. A lioness pursued an impala for at least {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}}, and  killed a young woman near her car.<ref>{{cite news |author=Torchia, C. |title=Lion kills woman at refuge of South African 'lion whisperer' |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/lion-kills-woman-at-refuge-of-south-african-lion-whisperer/2018/02/28/f1630a0c-1c6b-11e8-98f5-ceecfa8741b6_story.html |date=2018 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n* In July 2018, human remains were found in the lion enclosure of a privately owned reserve in South Africa. They were suspected to have been rhino poachers, as they had a high-powered rifle with a silencer, an axe and [[wire cutter]]s.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[BBC News|BBC]] |title=Lions eat 'rhino poachers' on South African game reserve |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44728507 |date=2018 |access-date=2018-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |image1=Taxidermy Lion Trophy Seized by U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Miami (37402001470).jpg |caption1=Taxidermied lion trophy seized by U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service in 2017}}\nIn Africa, lions are threatened by pre-emptive killing or in retaliation for preying on livestock. Prey base depletion, loss and conversion of habitat have led to a number of subpopulations becoming small and isolated. [[Trophy hunting]] has contributed to population declines in Botswana, Namibia, Zimbabwe and Zambia.<ref name=iucn/> It is the primary cause for a decline of lion populations in Tanzania's Selous Game Reserve and [[Katavi National Park]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Packer, C. |author2=Brink, H. |author3=Kissui, B. M. |author4=Maliti, H. |author5=Kushnir, H. |author6=Caro, T. |year=2011 |title=Effects of trophy hunting on lion and leopard populations in Tanzania |journal=Conservation Biology |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=142\u2013153 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2010.01576.x|pmid=20825444 }}</ref> Although lions and their prey are officially protected in Tsavo National Parks, they are regularly killed by local people, with over 100 known lion killings between 2001 and 2006.<ref name=\"Frank_al2006\"/>\n \nBetween 2008 and 2013, bones and body parts from at least 2621 individual lions were exported from South Africa to [[Southeast Asia]], and another 3437 lion skeletons between 2014 and 2016. Lion bones are used to replace [[tiger]] bones in [[traditional Asian medicine]]s.<ref name=\"Williams_al2017\">{{cite journal |author1=Williams, V. L. |author2=Loveridge, A. J. |author3=Newton, D. J. |author4=Macdonald, D. W. |title=A roaring trade? The legal trade in ''Panthera leo'' bones from Africa to East-Southeast Asia |journal=PLOS One |volume=12 |issue=10 |page=e0185996 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0185996 |pmid=29065143 |pmc=5655489 |bibcode=2017PLoSO..1285996W |year=2017}}</ref> Private game ranches in South Africa also breed lions for the [[canned hunt]]ing industry.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Schroeder |first=R. A. |year=2018 |title=Moving Targets: The 'Canned'Hunting of Captive-Bred Lions in South Africa |journal=African Studies Review |volume=61 |issue=1 |pages=8\u201332 |doi=10.1017/asr.2017.94}}</ref>\n \nIn 2014, seven lions in Ikona Wildlife Management Area were reportedly poisoned by a herdsman for attacking his [[cattle]].<ref name=\"Cable2018\">{{cite news |newspaper=The Cable |title='Herdsmen' poison lions, vultures \u2014 but not in Nigeria |url=https://www.thecable.ng/herdsmen-poison-lions-vultures-not-nigeria |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref> In February 2018, the carcasses of two male and four female lions were found dead in Ruaha National Park, and were suspected to have died of poisoning.<ref name=\"Observer2018\">{{cite news |author=Kamoga, J. |title=East African lions dying of poisoning |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |url=http://observer.ug/lifestyle/57009-east-african-lions-dying-of-poisoning.html |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref><ref name=\"Express2018\">{{cite news |author=Winter, S. |title=Lion MASSACRE as six big cats die after eating 'poison' |newspaper=[[Daily Express]] |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/nature/920088/lion-massacre-conservationists-poison-africa-Ruaha-National-Park |date=2018 |access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref>\n \nIn 2015 and 2017, two male lions, [[Cecil (lion)|Cecil]] and his son Xanda, were killed by trophy hunters in Zimbabwe's Hwange National Park.<ref name=\"BBC2015Cecil\">{{cite news |date=2015 |accessdate=3 August 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33674087 |title=Zimbabwe's 'iconic' lion Cecil killed by hunter |work=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728220149/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33674087 |archivedate=28 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Xanda, son of Cecil the lion, killed by hunter in Zimbabwe |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-40671590 |date=2017 |accessdate=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n \nUncontrolled bushfires and hunting of lions and prey species in Zambia's Kafue National Park make it difficult for the lion population to recover. Cub mortality in particular is high.<ref name=\"Midlane2013\">{{cite book |author=Midlane, N. |year=2013 |title=The conservation status and dynamics of a protected African lion ''Panthera leo'' population in Kafue National Park, Zambia |publisher=University of Cape Town |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\n{{multiple image |perrow=1 |image1=500px photo (177037413).jpeg |caption1=Lion cubs in Botswana}}\nAfrican lions are included in [[CITES Appendix II]]. Today, lion populations are stable only in large protected area complexes.<ref name=iucn/> [[IUCN]] regional offices and many wildlife conservation organisations cooperated to develop a Lion Conservation Strategy for Eastern and Southern Africa in 2006. The strategy envisages to maintain sufficient habitat, ensure a sufficient wild prey base, make lion-human coexistence sustainable and reduce factors that lead to further fragmentation of populations.<ref name=csg2006/>\nLocal communities in several Southern African lion range countries generate significant income through [[wildlife tourism]], which is a strong incentive for their support of conservation measures.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nEstablishing corridors between protected areas is important for facilitating dispersal of lions. [[Makgadikgadi Pans National Park]] and [[Central Kalahari Game Reserve]] are key dispersal areas in Southern Africa.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Cushman, S. A. |author2=Elliot, N. B. |author3=Bauer, D. |author4=Kesch, K. |author5=Bahaa-el-din, L. |author6=Bothwell, H. |display-authors=etal |year=2018 |title=Prioritizing core areas, corridors and conflict hotspots for Lion conservation in Southern Africa |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=13 |issue=7 |pages=e0196213 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0196213|pmid=29975694 |bibcode=2018PLoSO..1396213C }}</ref>\n\n=== In captivity ===\n{{multiple image |perrow=1\n|image1=MP-panthera leo krugeri 5.jpg |caption1=Captive lion in [[Philadelphia Zoo]]}}\n[[File:LionWalk.jpg|thumb|right|Tourist petting tame lions, [[Livingstone]], [[Zambia]]]]\nAt the beginning of the 21st century, the [[Addis Ababa Zoo]] kept 16 adult lions. It is assumed that their ancestors, five males and two females, were caught in southwestern Ethiopia as part of a zoological collection for Emperor [[Haile Selassie of Ethiopia|Haile Selassie I]].<ref name=Brucheetal2012>{{Cite journal |last=Bruche |first=S. |author2=Gusset, M. |author3=Lippold, S. |author4=Barnett, R. |author5=Eulenberger, K. |author6=Junhold, J. |author7=Driscoll, C. A. |author8= Hofreiter, M. |title=A genetically distinct lion (''Panthera leo'') population from Ethiopia |journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research |year=2012 |pages=215\u2013225 |doi=10.1007/s10344-012-0668-5 |volume=59 |issue=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Tefera |first=M. |title=Phenotypic and reproductive characteristics of lions (''Panthera leo'') at Addis Ababa Zoo |journal=Biodiversity & Conservation |volume=12 |issue=8 |pages=1629\u20131639 |year=2003 |doi=10.1023/A:1023641629538}}</ref>\n \nIn 2006, eight captive lions were registered under the name ''P. l. massaicus'', and 23 as ''P. l. nubicus'' from Tanzania by the [[International Species Information System]]; about 100 captive lions were registered  as ''P. l. krugeri'', which derived from lions captured in South Africa.<ref name=\"Barnett2006\"/>\n\nIn 2012, samples of lions kept at [[Sana'a Zoo]] in [[Yemen]] were found to cluster with those of lions from East and Southern Africa.<ref name=\"Bruche_al2012\">{{Cite journal |last=Bruche |first=S. |author2=Gusset, M. |author3=Lippold, S. |author4=Barnett, R. |author5=Eulenberger, K. |author6=Junhold, J. |author7=Driscoll, C. A. |author8=Hofreiter, M. |title=A genetically distinct lion (''Panthera leo'') population from Ethiopia |journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research |year=2012 |pages=215\u2013225 |doi=10.1007/s10344-012-0668-5 |volume=59 |issue=2}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural significance==\n[[File:Coat of Arms of the South African Republic.png|thumb|120px|The [[Coat of arms of South Africa]] featured a lion from 1910 to 1932]]\nThe lion is an animal symbol in [[shamanistic]] rituals of the [[Nuer people]]. In other East African cultures, it symbolizes laziness.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hogarth |first=C. |last2=Butler |first2=N. |year=2004 |title=Shamanism: An Encyclopedia of World Beliefs, Practices, and Culture, Volume 1 |editor=Walter, M. N. |isbn=978-1-57607-645-3 |chapter=Animal Symbolism (Africa) |pages=[https://archive.org/details/shamanism00mari/page/3 3\u20136] |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=X8waCmzjiD4C&pg=PA3&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj916XT2OjjAhWG16QKHaj5A6kQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&f=false |url=https://archive.org/details/shamanism00mari/page/3 }}</ref> Scars inflicted by lions are regarded as a sign of courage among the [[Masai people]].<ref name=\"Lynch2004\">{{cite book |last=Lynch |first=P. A. |year=2004 |title=African Mythology A to Z |publisher=Infobase Publishing |page=[https://archive.org/details/africanmythology00lync_0/page/63 63] |isbn=978-0-8160-4892-2 |chapter=Lion |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/africanmythology00lync_0/page/63 |url=https://archive.org/details/africanmythology00lync_0/page/63 }}</ref>\nThe name '[[Simba]]' is a [[Swahili language|Swahili]] word for the lion, which also means 'aggressive', 'king' and 'strong'.<ref>{{cite book |author=Brakefield, T. |title=Big Cats: Kingdom of Might |publisher=Voyageur Press |url=https://archive.org/details/bigcatskingdomof0000brak |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/bigcatskingdomof0000brak/page/44 44] |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-89658-329-0}}</ref>\n\n==Regional names==\nLion populations in Southern and East Africa were referred to by several regional names, including Katanga lion, Transvaal lion, Kalahari lion,<ref name=\"L\u00f6nnberg1914\" /><ref name=Roberts1929/><ref name=Roberts1948/> Southeast African lion, and Southwest African lion,<ref name=\"Jackson2010\">{{cite book |last=Jackson |first=D. |title=Lion |chapter=Introduction |pages=1\u201321 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=65lK7UIVRfIC&pg |publisher=[[Reaktion Books]] |location=[[London]] |isbn=978-1861897350 |date=2010}}</ref> Masai lion, Serengeti lion,<ref name=Schaller72/> Tsavo lion<ref name=\"Borzo2002\">{{cite news |last=Borzo |first=G. |title=Unique social system found in famous Tsavo lions |url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2002-04/fm-uss040802.php |newspaper=EurekAlert |year=2002}}</ref> and Uganda lion.<ref name=Hemmer1974/> It has also been referred to as 'Eastern-Southern African lion',<ref name=\"Barnett_al2006Origin\"/> 'Southern lion',<ref name=\"Agostinho_al2008\"/> and as 'southern subspecies'.<ref name=\"Hunter2018\">{{cite book |last1=Hunter |first1=L. |author-link=Luke Hunter |last2=Barrett |first2=P. |title=The Field Guide to Carnivores of the World |edition=Second |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London, Oxford, New York, New Delhi, Sydney |isbn=978-1-4729-5080-2 |date=2018 |chapter=Lion ''Panthera leo'' |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4HpxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&f=false |pages=46\u221247}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*Wild cats in Africa: [[African leopard]] {{\u00b7}} [[African golden cat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Caracal]] {{\u00b7}} [[Serval]] {{\u00b7}} [[African wildcat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Sand cat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Black-footed cat]] {{\u00b7}} [[Cheetah]]\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Elsa the lioness]]\n*''[[Born Free]]''\n*[[Mapogo lion coalition]]\n*''[[The Lion King]]''\n*''[[Pride (2004 film)]]''\n*''[[African Cats]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n \n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Lions of Southern Africa}}\n{{Commons category|Lions of Southeast Africa}}\n*{{cite news |author=Carrington, D. |date=2018 |title=Lion poaching: the brutal new threat to Africa's prides |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/nov/05/lion-poaching-the-brutal-new-threat-to-africas-prides}}\n*{{cite web |title=Lion (''Panthera leo'' ssp. ''melanochaita'') |year=2016 |website=ECOS Environmental Conservation Online System |url=https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?sId=9519}}\n*[http://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Fund-to-stop-the-decline-in-the-population-of-African-lions/4552908-4587534-pty9m/index.html $0.5m funding to stop the decline in the population of African lions]\n*[https://africageographic.com/blog/what-will-it-take-to-save-the-east-african-lion-from-extinction-hunting-or-herding/ What Will It Take to Save the East African Lion from Extinction? Hunting or Herding?]\n*[http://leofoundation.org/en/projects/lions-in-east-africa/ Lions in East Africa]\n*[https://phys.org/news/2018-02-recovering-population-zimbabwean-african-lions.html Recovering population of Zimbabwean African lions show low genetic diversity]\n*[https://petapixel.com/2018/09/04/lioness-steals-photographers-