{"title_page": "Pierre Morel (cyclist)", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierre Morel\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1930|9|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = Saint-Claude, France\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Pierre Morel''' (born 10 September 1930) is a French former professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=33276 |title=Pierre Morel |accessdate=12 July 2016 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He rode in the [[1960 Tour de France]].<ref name=\"mdc1960\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=47\u00e8me Tour de France 1960|language=French|accessdate=11 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121063116/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|archivedate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling archives|33276}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morel, Pierre}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierre Morel\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1930|9|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = Saint-Claude, France\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Pierre Morel''' (born 10 September 1930) is a French former professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=33276 |title=Pierre Morel |accessdate=12 July 2016 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He rode in the [[1960 Tour de France]].<ref name=\"mdc1960\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=47\u00e8me Tour de France 1960|language=French|accessdate=11 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121063116/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1960.php|archivedate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling archives|33276}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morel, Pierre}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Morel_(cyclist)"}
{"title_page": "The Accidental Billionaires", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name = The Accidental Billionaires\n| image = The Accidental Billionaires.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| author = Ben Mezrich\n| illustrator = \n| cover_artist = \n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Facebook]]\n| genre = [[Non-fiction]]\n| publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| pub_date = {{Start date|2009|07|14}}\n| media_type = Print\n| pages = 260\n| isbn = 978-0-385-52937-2\n| oclc = 422928345\n}}\n\n'''''The Accidental Billionaires: The Founding of Facebook, a Tale of Sex, Money, Genius, and Betrayal''''' is a 2009 book by [[Ben Mezrich]] about the founding of [[Facebook]],<ref name=moneycnn>{{cite web|last=Hempel |first=Jessi |url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/06/25/technology/founding_of_facebook.fortune/index.htm |title=The Book that Facebook Doesn't Want You to Read|publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2009-06-25 |accessdate=2010-07-10}}</ref> adapted by [[Columbia Pictures]] for the 2010 film ''[[The Social Network]]''. Co-founder Eduardo Saverin served as Mezrich's main consultant,<ref name=moneycnn /> although declined to speak with him while the book was being researched. After Zuckerberg and Saverin settled their lawsuit, Saverin broke off contact with the author.\n\n== Sources ==\nBen Mezrich maintains that the book is not a work of fiction despite his narrative style of writing. Some of his sources are his conversations with Facebook co-founder Eduardo Saverin and the court documents made available to him because of \"all these college kids suing each other.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conspiracyworldwide.podomatic.com/entry/2010-10-23T08_05_51-07_00 |title=Podomatic interview with Ben Mezrich}}</ref><ref>[[Janet Maslin|Maslin, Janet]]. (2009-07-19). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/20/books/20maslin.html \"Harvard Pals Grow Rich: Chronicling Facebook Without Face Time\"] at ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''.</ref>\n\n== Content ==\nThe story begins in the weeks that precede the launch of \"thefacebook.com\" at Harvard.  Eduardo Saverin, cast as the protagonist, has befriended Mark Zuckerberg, and both struggle for social acceptance\u2014Saverin by joining a [[final club]], Zuckerberg by creating a website where girls can be ranked according to their looks.  Zuckerberg's stunt, though successful, puts him at odds with the Harvard Administrative Board, and has angered numerous campus women's groups as well as individual female students.  An article on the incident in ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'' is noticed by three Harvard seniors: [[Winklevoss twins|twin brothers]] [[Cameron Winklevoss|Cameron]] and [[Tyler Winklevoss]] and [[Divya Narendra]], who are trying to launch a Harvard dating site. The trio approaches Zuckerberg, convincing him to join in the venture. Zuckerberg, however, feels their site does not have what he thinks is the right approach and begins developing thefacebook with financial help from Saverin and programming from Zuckerberg's roommates.\n\nOnce thefacebook.com is launched it becomes an immediate hit on campus. After discovering what Zuckerberg has done, the Winklevosses and Narendra are infuriated and seek legal advice from their father's lawyer.  The story then chronicles the changing relationship between Saverin and Zuckerberg, who have different visions for thefacebook.\n\nWhile the first half of the book centers on the Harvard University campus and focuses on college life, the second half centers on the business end of thefacebook and Zuckerberg's move to [[Silicon Valley]].  [[Napster]] creator [[Sean Parker]] inserts himself into Zuckerberg's life, soon becoming a mentor to Zuckerberg who guides him to Silicon Valley venture capitalists and other players in the industry. Saverin, having graduated from Harvard, continues to feel sidelined by Parker, who he feels is not the best influence on Zuckerberg and is replacing him in importance to the advancement of thefacebook. The book does not provide a conclusion since, according to the author, the issues were still being disputed in court.\n\n== Film adaptation ==\n[[Columbia Pictures]] released a film adaptation of the book in 2010 titled ''[[The Social Network]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Leah McLaren|McLaren, Leah]] |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/style/zuckerpunched-maybe-those-tech-nerds-arent-so-harmless/article1577360 |title=Zuckerpunched! Maybe Those Tech Nerds Aren't so Harmless |publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date= |accessdate=2010-07-10}}</ref> Directed by [[David Fincher]] with the screenplay written by [[Aaron Sorkin]], the film stars [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Andrew Garfield]], [[Armie Hammer]], and [[Justin Timberlake]].  Sorkin's script won the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>Harris, Paul. (2009-07-05). [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/jul/05/facebook-accidental-billionaires-zuckerberg \"A sexy saga of Facebook's birth - but is it fantasy?\"] at [[Guardian.co.uk]]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Internet|Books}}\n* {{Facebook|id=The-Accidental-Billionaires-by-Ben-Mezrich/64052888061|name=''The Accidental Billionaires: The Founding of Facebook, a Tale of Sex, Money, Genius, and Betrayal''}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=1cw8AJTBbZMC&printsec=frontcover ''The Accidental Billionaires'' preview] at [[Google Books]]\n* [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203946904574302553656791762 ''The Accidental Billionaires'' review - \"Glancing At Facebook\"] by [[Paul Boutin (journalist)|Paul Boutin]] at ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n* [http://www.factbehindfiction.com/index_files/facebook.htm ''Facebook in Popular Culture'']\n*[http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Mez ''After Words'' interview with Mezrich on ''The Accidental Billionaires'', August 10, 2009]\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Ben Mezrich}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Accidental Billionaires, The}}\n[[Category:2009 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American biographies]]\n[[Category:Books about computer and internet entrepreneurs]]\n[[Category:Books adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Works about Facebook]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name = The Accidental Billionaires\n| image = The Accidental Billionaires.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| author = Ben Mezrich\n| illustrator = \n| cover_artist = \n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Facebook]]\n| genre = [[Non-fiction]]\n| publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| pub_date = {{Start date|2009|07|14}}\n| media_type = Print\n| pages = 260\n| isbn = 978-0-385-52937-2\n| oclc = 422928345\n}}\n\n'''''The Accidental Billionaires: The Founding of Facebook, a Tale of Sex, Money, Genius, and Betrayal''''' is a 2009 book by [[Ben Mezrich]] about the founding of [[Facebook]],<ref name=moneycnn>{{cite web|last=Hempel |first=Jessi |url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/06/25/technology/founding_of_facebook.fortune/index.htm |title=The Book that Facebook Doesn't Want You to Read|publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2009-06-25 |accessdate=2010-07-10}}</ref> adapted by [[Columbia Pictures]] for the 2010 film ''[[The Social Network]]''. Co Founder Eduardo Saverin served as Mezrich's main consultant,<ref name=moneycnn /> although declined to speak with him while the book was being researched. After Zuckerberg and Saverin settled their lawsuit, Saverin broke off contact with the author.\n\n== Sources ==\nBen Mezrich maintains that the book is not a work of fiction despite his narrative style of writing. Some of his sources are his conversations with Facebook co-founder Eduardo Saverin and the court documents made available to him because of \"all these college kids suing each other.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conspiracyworldwide.podomatic.com/entry/2010-10-23T08_05_51-07_00 |title=Podomatic interview with Ben Mezrich}}</ref><ref>[[Janet Maslin|Maslin, Janet]]. (2009-07-19). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/20/books/20maslin.html \"Harvard Pals Grow Rich: Chronicling Facebook Without Face Time\"] at ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''.</ref>\n\n== Content ==\nThe story begins in the weeks that precede the launch of \"thefacebook.com\" at Harvard.  Eduardo Saverin, cast as the protagonist, has befriended Mark Zuckerberg, and both struggle for social acceptance\u2014Saverin by joining a [[final club]], Zuckerberg by creating a website where girls can be ranked according to their looks.  Zuckerberg's stunt, though successful, puts him at odds with the Harvard Administrative Board, and has angered numerous campus women's groups as well as individual female students.  An article on the incident in ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'' is noticed by three Harvard seniors: [[Winklevoss twins|twin brothers]] [[Cameron Winklevoss|Cameron]] and [[Tyler Winklevoss]] and [[Divya Narendra]], who are trying to launch a Harvard dating site. The trio approaches Zuckerberg, convincing him to join in the venture. Zuckerberg, however, feels their site does not have what he thinks is the right approach and begins developing thefacebook with financial help from Saverin and programming from Zuckerberg's roommates.\n\nOnce thefacebook.com is launched it becomes an immediate hit on campus. After discovering what Zuckerberg has done, the Winklevosses and Narendra are infuriated and seek legal advice from their father's lawyer.  The story then chronicles the changing relationship between Saverin and Zuckerberg, who have different visions for thefacebook.\n\nWhile the first half of the book centers on the Harvard University campus and focuses on college life, the second half centers on the business end of thefacebook and Zuckerberg's move to [[Silicon Valley]].  [[Napster]] creator [[Sean Parker]] inserts himself into Zuckerberg's life, soon becoming a mentor to Zuckerberg who guides him to Silicon Valley venture capitalists and other players in the industry. Saverin, having graduated from Harvard, continues to feel sidelined by Parker, who he feels is not the best influence on Zuckerberg and is replacing him in importance to the advancement of thefacebook. The book does not provide a conclusion since, according to the author, the issues were still being disputed in court.\n\n== Film adaptation ==\n[[Columbia Pictures]] released a film adaptation of the book in 2010 titled ''[[The Social Network]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Leah McLaren|McLaren, Leah]] |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/style/zuckerpunched-maybe-those-tech-nerds-arent-so-harmless/article1577360 |title=Zuckerpunched! Maybe Those Tech Nerds Aren't so Harmless |publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date= |accessdate=2010-07-10}}</ref> Directed by [[David Fincher]] with the screenplay written by [[Aaron Sorkin]], the film stars [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Andrew Garfield]], [[Armie Hammer]], and [[Justin Timberlake]].  Sorkin's script won the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>Harris, Paul. (2009-07-05). [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/jul/05/facebook-accidental-billionaires-zuckerberg \"A sexy saga of Facebook's birth - but is it fantasy?\"] at [[Guardian.co.uk]]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Internet|Books}}\n* {{Facebook|id=The-Accidental-Billionaires-by-Ben-Mezrich/64052888061|name=''The Accidental Billionaires: The Founding of Facebook, a Tale of Sex, Money, Genius, and Betrayal''}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=1cw8AJTBbZMC&printsec=frontcover ''The Accidental Billionaires'' preview] at [[Google Books]]\n* [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203946904574302553656791762 ''The Accidental Billionaires'' review - \"Glancing At Facebook\"] by [[Paul Boutin (journalist)|Paul Boutin]] at ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n* [http://www.factbehindfiction.com/index_files/facebook.htm ''Facebook in Popular Culture'']\n*[http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Mez ''After Words'' interview with Mezrich on ''The Accidental Billionaires'', August 10, 2009]\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Ben Mezrich}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Accidental Billionaires, The}}\n[[Category:2009 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American biographies]]\n[[Category:Books about computer and internet entrepreneurs]]\n[[Category:Books adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Works about Facebook]]\n", "name_user": "Packer1028", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Accidental_Billionaires"}
{"title_page": "Aaron Taylor-Johnson", "text_new": "{{Short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n| image              = Aaron Taylor-Johnson SDCC 2014 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Johnson at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic Con]]\n| birth_name         = Aaron Perry Johnson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|6|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire, England\n| nationality        = British\n| othername          = Aaron Johnson\n| occupation         = Actor, screenwriter\n| years_active       = 2000\u2013present\n| children           = 2\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]]|2012}}\n}}\n'''Aaron Perry Taylor-Johnson''' (n\u00e9 '''Johnson''';<ref name=birth>''Births, Marriages & Deaths Index of England & Wales, 1916\u20132005.''; at ancestry.com</ref> born 13 June 1990)<ref name=TimesOnline/><ref name=UKTVGuide/> is an English<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/aaron-taylor-johnson-i-was-raised-by-women-now-i-m-raising-women-and-sam-s-the-best-woman-i-know-9323936.html|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'I was raised by women. Now I\u2019m raising women. And Sam's the best woman I know'|work=London Evening Standard|date=8 May 2014|last=Rafanelli|first=Stephanie|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> actor and screenwriter, best known for his portrayal of the [[Kick-Ass (character)|titular character]] in the ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'' films and [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015).\n\nTaylor-Johnson began performing at age six and has appeared in films such as ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'' (2003), playing a young [[Charlie Chaplin]], ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'' (2006) and ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'' (2008). He had his breakthrough performance in the [[John Lennon]] biopic ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' (2009). He went on to portray Ben in the [[Oliver Stone]]-directed crime thriller ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'' (2012), Russian aristocrat Count Vronsky in [[Joe Wright]]'s adaptation of ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]'' (2012) and Lt. Brody in [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]' monster movie ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' (2014). For his performance as psychopathic drifter Ray Marcus in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]'' (2016), he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]].\n\n==Early life==\nAaron Perry Johnson was born in [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/893722/Aaron-Johnson/biography |title= Aaron Johnson biography |work= NYTimes.com Movies & TV |publisher= [[The New York Times]] ([[AllMovie|All Movie Guide]] and [[Baseline (database)|Baseline]]) |accessdate= 29 October 2011}}</ref> the son of Sarah and Robert Johnson, a [[housewife]] mother and civil engineer father, respectively.<ref name=UKTVGuide>{{cite web|url=http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130913180604/http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=Aaron Johnson profile|publisher=Uk-tv-guide.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"timesref02\">{{cite news|last=Maher|first=Kevin|title=Aaron Johnson: Beatle mania|newspaper=The Times|date=3 October 2009|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/london_film_festival/article6852334.ece?print=yes&randnum=1151003209000|accessdate=24 April 2010|location=London}}</ref> He has a sister, Gemma, who appeared in his film ''[[Tom & Thomas]]'' (2002) in a small role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://myeveryzine.com/story/10-things-know-about-aaron-johnson/|title=10 Things to Know About Aaron Johnson|first=Grace|last=Gavilanes|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> He is [[British Jews|Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/23/aaron-taylor-johnson-avengers-age-ultron-interview | title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'Changing my name felt beautiful' | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=23 April 2015 | accessdate=9 August 2015 | author=Gilbey, Ryan|quote=He liked it recently when someone said he resembled a fashionable Hasidic Jew. \u201cThat was nice because I have really curly hair and also I\u2019m Jewish,\u201d he explains.}}</ref> He was educated at [[Holmer Green Senior School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404070713/http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|url-status=dead|title=Hgss.co.uk|archivedate=4 April 2015}}</ref> and attended the Jackie Palmer Stage School in High Wycombe between 1996 and 2008, where he studied drama, tap, jazz, acrobatics, and singing.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Cain |title=Another successful year for the Jackie Palmer Stage School and agency|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/news/4829177.Wycombe_s_stage_school_s_pupils_star_on_TV/ |newspaper=[[Bucks Free Press]] |date=3 January 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTaylor-Johnson began acting at the age of six. On stage, he appeared in a London production of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Macbeth]]'', playing the son of [[Macduff (Macbeth)|Macduff]] alongside [[Rufus Sewell]], who played [[Macbeth]], in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sewell to Return to Stage in Macbeth |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |archivedate=12 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130412044133/http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |url-status=dead |access-date=16 February 2013 }}</ref> He appeared in [[Arthur Miller]]\u2019s ''[[All My Sons]]'' in 2000. His television roles have included Niker in the 2004 [[BBC]] adaptation of the novel ''[[Feather Boy]]'', Aaron in [[Danny Brocklehurst]]'s [[ITV1]] serial ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]'', and Owen Stephens in ''[[Nearly Famous]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6953190.ece|title=The Times: Entertainment|work=The Times|accessdate=26 October 2011|location=London|first=Sadie |last=Gray}}</ref> In 2003, Taylor-Johnson appeared as a young [[Charlie Chaplin]] in ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'', with Chaplin depicted as a member of a London gang of street thugs. In 2006, he appeared in ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'', appearing in the early flashback scenes as [[Edward Norton]]'s character, Eduard Abramovicz, as a teenager. The scenes show the young Eduard as he first learns magic, and to do this, Johnson had to learn how to perform the ball trick displayed by his character. He learned how to perform the balancing of the egg on the stick, although that was effected mechanically.<ref>Writer/director [[Neil Burger]] explains this on the film's DVD commentary.</ref> Also in 2006, he starred in the film ''[[The Thief Lord (film)|The Thief Lord]]'', as Prosper.\n[[File:Aaron Taylor-Johnson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Johnson at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla'']]'']]\nTaylor-Johnson appeared as [[John Lennon]] in the 2009 biographical film film ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', directed by [[Sam Taylor-Wood]]. His performance saw him receive the [[Empire Award for Best Newcomer]] and he was also nominated for [[London Film Critics Circle Awards 2009#Young British Performer of the Year|Young British Performer of the Year]] by the [[London Film Critics' Circle]]. In 2010, Taylor-Johnson appeared as [[Kick-Ass (character)|David \"Dave\" Lizewski/Kick-Ass]], the lead character in ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'', based on the [[Kick-Ass (comic)|superhero comic book of the same name]] by Scottish writer [[Mark Millar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/43367 |title=Ain't It Cool News: The best in movie, TV, DVD, and comic book news |publisher=Aintitcool.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gholson|first=John |url=http://www.scifisquad.com/2009/12/14/kick-ass-kicks-ass-at-bnat|title='Kick-Ass' Kicks Ass at BNAT \u2013 The Moviefone Blog|publisher=Scifisquad.com|date=2 May 2011|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> His performance in ''Kick-Ass'' saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]. He has also appeared as the central character, William, in [[Hideo Nakata]]'s ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline/> In December 2010, Taylor-Johnson joined the cast of ''[[Albert Nobbs]]'' as a replacement for [[Orlando Bloom]], who dropped out of the production due to his wife's pregnancy.<ref name=nobbs>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|url=http://www.thewrap.com/node/23054|title=Aaron Johnson Joins Mia Wasikowska in 'Albert Nobbs'|publisher=Thewrap.com|date=6 December 2010|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in [[R.E.M.]]'s 2011 music video \"[[\u00dcberlin]]\", which was also directed by his then-fianc\u00e9e.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2011/mar/02/rem-uberlin|title=Watch REM's Uberlin, starring Aaron Johnson \u2013 video|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=4 December 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Taylor-Johnson played Count Vronsky in ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''. Later that year, he starred as Ben in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''. [[HitFix]] film critic Drew McWeeny was positive of the bond between Johnson and co-star [[Taylor Kitsch]], which \"seems not only credible but lived in and authentic throughout the film\", and noted the evolution in maturity of Johnson since ''Kick-Ass''.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny|first=Drew|title=Review: Oliver Stone turns Aaron Johnson, Taylor Kitsch, and Blake Lively into 'Savages'|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-oliver-stone-turns-aaron-johnson-taylor-kitsch-and-blake-lively-into-savages|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=30 June 2012}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in the ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' reboot, released in May 2014.<ref name=\"Godzilla1\">{{cite web|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |title=Elizabeth Olsen, Bryan Cranston circling 'Godzilla' |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=13 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313184951/http://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Godzilla2\">{{cite web |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story |title='Godzilla' trailer: Bryan Cranston panics, destruction rains down |last=Gettell |first=Oliver |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=26 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226182729/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story#axzz2wDzJjMw7 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson played [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), the sequel to ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]''.<ref name=\"AgeofUltron\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |title=Official: Elizabeth Olsen & Aaron Taylor-Johnson Join 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' |publisher=Marvel |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=25 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108033705/http://marvel.com/news/movies/2013/11/25/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |archivedate=8 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson first appeared as the character in a post-credits scene of the film ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''.<ref name=\"WinterSoldier\">{{cite web|first=Jenna |last=Milly |date=14 March 2014 |title='Captain America: The Winter Soldier' premiere: Crossover is the word |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=15 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315010847/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The role reunited him with [[Elizabeth Olsen]], who played his wife in ''Godzilla''.<ref name=\"Godzilla2\" /><ref name=\"AgeofUltron\" />\n\nIn 2016, he played Ray, a menacing Texan, in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''. For the role, he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]. Taylor-Johnson also became first Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor winner since [[Richard Benjamin]] who did not receive an [[Academy Award]] nomination. For the role he also received a nomination for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]. In 2017, he played an American soldier (alongside [[John Cena]]) in [[Doug Liman]]'s thriller ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson Eyed for Lead in Doug Liman's 'The Wall' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/aaron-taylor-johnson-the-wall-doug-liman-1201769484/|accessdate=1 December 2016|work=Variety|date=9 May 2016}}</ref> and in 2018, he appeared in ''[[Outlaw King]]'', a British-American historical action drama about [[Robert the Bruce]] and the Wars of Scottish Independence. In May 2019, Taylor-Johnson was cast in [[Christopher Nolan]]\u2019s ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'', set for release in July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/christopher-nolan-tenet-movie-cast-release-date-1202620596/|title=Christopher Nolan's New Movie Gets A Title, Final Cast As Shooting Begins|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, it was announced that Aaron Taylor Johnson will join [[Steve Pemberton]] on West End stage in [[The Pillowman]] play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/west-end-aaron-taylor-johnson-steve-pemberton-to-star-in-the-pillowman/|title=\nWest End: Aaron Taylor-Johnson & Steve Pemberton to Star in The Pillowman|publisher=Ikon London Magazine| first1 = Tamara|last1=Orlova-Alvarez | date=28 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> directed by Matthew Dunster.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sam Taylor-Wood & Aaron Johnson.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Taylor-Johnson, with Sam Taylor-Johnson, in September 2010]]\nAaron Johnson began a relationship with ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' director [[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]], after meeting on the 2009 set of the film when he was 18 and she was 42.<ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\"/> They announced their engagement in October 2009 and married at [[Babington House]], Somerset, England on 21 June 2012. The two changed their surnames to \"Taylor-Johnson\" and use the surname professionally.<ref name=\"Buchanan\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/aaron-johnson-sam-taylor-wood-marry.html |title=Aaron Johnson, Sam Taylor-Wood Marry |publisher=Vulture |accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20363616,00.html|title=She's Having His Baby!|magazine=People|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=25 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |title=50 Shades of Grey film to be directed by Sam Taylor-Johnson |work=Shepton Mallet Journal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522213458/http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |archivedate=22 May 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/6664818/Aaron-Johnson-fiance-of-artist-Sam-Taylor-Wood-considers-himself-a-very-lucky-man.html|title=Aaron Johnson, fianc\u00e9 of artist Sam Taylor-Wood, considers himself 'a very lucky man'|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=27 November 2009|accessdate=25 January 2012|location=London}}</ref> The couple have two daughters. He is also stepfather to two daughters from his wife's previous marriage.\n\nTaylor-Johnson was named one of [[GQ]]'s 50 best dressed British men in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 Best Dressed Men in Britain 2015 |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015/ |work=GQ |date=5 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107145128/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015 |archivedate=7 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Denotes works that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Apocalypse (2000 film)|The Apocalypse]]''\n| Johanan\n| Raffaele Mertes\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Tom & Thomas]]''\n| Tom Sheppard / Thomas\n| Esm\u00e9 Lammers\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2003\n| ''[[Behind Closed Doors (2003 film)|Behind Closed Doors]]''\n| Sam Goodwin\n| Louis Caulfield\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Shanghai Knights]]''\n| [[Charlie Chaplin]]\n| [[David Dobkin (director)|David Dobkin]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Dead Cool]]''\n| George\n| David Cohen\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2006\n| ''{{sortname|The|Thief Lord|dab=film}}''\n| Prosper\n| Richard Claus\n|\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Illusionist|dab=2006 film}}''\n| Young Eisenheim\n| [[Neil Burger]]\n|\n|-\n| ''Fast Learners''\n| Neil\n| [[Christoph R\u00f6hl]]\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Best Man|The Best Man (2005 film)}}''\n| Michael (Aged 15)\n| Stefan Schwartz\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''The Magic Door''\n| Flip\n| Paul Matthews\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008\n| ''Dummy''\n| Danny\n| Matthew Thompson\n| Nominated \u2014 [[London Film Critics' Circle|ALFS Award for Young British Performer of the Year]]\n|-\n| ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]''\n| Robbie Jennings\n| [[Gurinder Chadha]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2009\n| ''{{sortname|The|Greatest|dab=2009 film}}''\n| Bennett Brewer\n| [[Shana Feste]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Nowhere Boy]]''\n| [[John Lennon]]\n| [[Sam Taylor-Johnson]]\n| [[Empire Award for Best Newcomer]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[London Film Critics' Circle|ALFS Award for Young British Performer of the Year]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[British Independent Film Awards|British Independent Film Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2010\n| ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]''\n| [[Kick-Ass (character)|David \"Dave\" Lizewski / Kick-Ass]]\n| [[Matthew Vaughn]]\n| Nominated \u2014 [[Empire Award for Best Actor]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Breakout Performance \u2013 Male]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Fantasy Actor]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Superhero]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award for Breakout Male]]\n|-\n| ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''\n| William Collins\n| [[Hideo Nakata]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Albert Nobbs]]''\n| Joe Mackins\n| [[Rodrigo Garc\u00eda (director)|Rodrigo Garc\u00eda]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''\n| Ben\n| [[Oliver Stone]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''\n| Count Vronsky\n| [[Joe Wright]]\n| Final time credited as Aaron Johnson<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] Award for Best Depiction of Nudity, Sexuality, or Seduction <small>(shared w/ [[Keira Knightley]])</small>\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Kick-Ass 2 (film)|Kick-Ass 2]]''\n| David \"Dave\" Lizewski / Kick-Ass\n| [[Jeff Wadlow]]\n| First time credited as Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n| ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''\n| [[Quicksilver (comics)|Pietro Maximoff / Quicksilver]]\n| [[Russo brothers|Anthony and Joe Russo]]\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]''\n| Lt. Ford Brody\n| [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]''\n|Pietro Maximoff / Quicksilver\n| [[Joss Whedon]]\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''\n| Ray Marcus\n| [[Tom Ford]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]<br>[[Santa Barbara International Film Festival|Virtuosos Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]''\n| Sgt. Allen \"Ize\" Isaac\n| [[Doug Liman]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| ''[[Outlaw King]]''\n| [[James Douglas, Lord of Douglas]]\n| [[David Mackenzie (director)|David Mackenzie]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[A Million Little Pieces (film)|A Million Little Pieces]]''\n| [[James Frey]]\n| Sam Taylor-Johnson\n| Also writer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\n|data-sort-value=\"King's Man, The\" scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The King's Man]]''{{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Lee Unwin\n|Matthew Vaughn\n|Post-production\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]''{{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n| TBA\n| [[Christopher Nolan]]\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Armadillo''\n| Young Lorimer Black\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|Bill}}''\n| Zac Clough\n| Episode: \"162\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2004\n| ''Family Business''\n| Paul Sullivan\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Feather Boy]]''\n| Niker\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2006\n| ''[[I Shouldn't Be Alive]]''\n| Mark\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Joey Byrne\n| Episode: \"Silent Ties\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2007\n| ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]''\n| Aaron\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Coming Up (TV series)|Coming Up]]''\n| Eoin\n| Episode: \"99,100\"\n|-\n| ''[[Nearly Famous]]''\n| Owen Stephens\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Sherlock Holmes and the Baker Street Irregulars]]''\n| Finch\n| Television film\n|-\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Kick-Ass: The Game]]''\n| Kick-Ass (voice)\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n|list =\n{{Empire Award for Best Newcomer}}\n{{Glamour Awards Man of the Year}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Supporting Actor Motion Picture}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor-Johnson, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Newcomer Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish English male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n| image              = Aaron Taylor-Johnson SDCC 2014 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Johnson at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic Con]]\n| birth_name         = Aaron Perry Johnson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|6|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire, England\n| nationality        = British\n| othername          = Aaron Johnson\n| occupation         = Actor, screenwriter\n| years_active       = 2000\u2013present\n| children           = 2\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]]|2012}}\n}}\n'''Aaron Perry Taylor-Johnson''' (n\u00e9 '''Johnson''';<ref name=birth>''Births, Marriages & Deaths Index of England & Wales, 1916\u20132005.''; at ancestry.com</ref> born 13 June 1990)<ref name=TimesOnline/><ref name=UKTVGuide/> is an English<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/aaron-taylor-johnson-i-was-raised-by-women-now-i-m-raising-women-and-sam-s-the-best-woman-i-know-9323936.html|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'I was raised by women. Now I\u2019m raising women. And Sam's the best woman I know'|work=London Evening Standard|date=8 May 2014|last=Rafanelli|first=Stephanie|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> actor and screenwriter, best known for his portrayal of the [[Kick-Ass (character)|titular character]] in the ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'' films and [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015).\n\nTaylor-Johnson began performing at age six and has appeared in films such as ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'' (2003), playing a young [[Charlie Chaplin]], ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'' (2006) and ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'' (2008). He had his breakthrough performance in the [[John Lennon]] biopic ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' (2009). He went on to portray Ben in the [[Oliver Stone]]-directed crime thriller ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'' (2012), Russian aristocrat Count Vronsky in [[Joe Wright]]'s adaptation of ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]'' (2012) and Lt. Brody in [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]' monster movie ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' (2014). For his performance as psychopathic drifter Ray Marcus in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]'' (2016), he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]].\n\n==Early life==\nAaron Perry Johnson was born in [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/893722/Aaron-Johnson/biography |title= Aaron Johnson biography |work= NYTimes.com Movies & TV |publisher= [[The New York Times]] ([[AllMovie|All Movie Guide]] and [[Baseline (database)|Baseline]]) |accessdate= 29 October 2011}}</ref> the son of Sarah and Robert Johnson, a [[housewife]] mother and civil engineer father, respectively.<ref name=UKTVGuide>{{cite web|url=http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130913180604/http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=Aaron Johnson profile|publisher=Uk-tv-guide.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"timesref02\">{{cite news|last=Maher|first=Kevin|title=Aaron Johnson: Beatle mania|newspaper=The Times|date=3 October 2009|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/london_film_festival/article6852334.ece?print=yes&randnum=1151003209000|accessdate=24 April 2010|location=London}}</ref> He has a sister, Gemma, who appeared in his film ''[[Tom & Thomas]]'' (2002) in a small role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://myeveryzine.com/story/10-things-know-about-aaron-johnson/|title=10 Things to Know About Aaron Johnson|first=Grace|last=Gavilanes|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> He is [[British Jews|Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/23/aaron-taylor-johnson-avengers-age-ultron-interview | title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'Changing my name felt beautiful' | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=23 April 2015 | accessdate=9 August 2015 | author=Gilbey, Ryan|quote=He liked it recently when someone said he resembled a fashionable Hasidic Jew. \u201cThat was nice because I have really curly hair and also I\u2019m Jewish,\u201d he explains.}}</ref> He was educated at [[Holmer Green Senior School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404070713/http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|url-status=dead|title=Hgss.co.uk|archivedate=4 April 2015}}</ref> and attended the Jackie Palmer Stage School in High Wycombe between 1996 and 2008, where he studied drama, tap, jazz, acrobatics, and singing.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Cain |title=Another successful year for the Jackie Palmer Stage School and agency|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/news/4829177.Wycombe_s_stage_school_s_pupils_star_on_TV/ |newspaper=[[Bucks Free Press]] |date=3 January 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTaylor-Johnson began acting at the age of six. On stage, he appeared in a London production of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Macbeth]]'', playing the son of [[Macduff (Macbeth)|Macduff]] alongside [[Rufus Sewell]], who played [[Macbeth]], in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sewell to Return to Stage in Macbeth |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |archivedate=12 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130412044133/http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |url-status=dead  |access-date=16 February 2013 }}</ref> He appeared in [[Arthur Miller]]\u2019s ''[[All My Sons]]'' in 2000. His television roles have included Niker in the 2004 [[BBC]] adaptation of the novel ''[[Feather Boy]]'', Aaron in [[Danny Brocklehurst]]'s [[ITV1]] serial ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]'', and Owen Stephens in ''[[Nearly Famous]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6953190.ece|title=The Times: Entertainment|work=The Times|accessdate=26 October 2011|location=London|first=Sadie |last=Gray}}</ref> In 2003, Taylor-Johnson appeared as a young [[Charlie Chaplin]] in ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'', with Chaplin depicted as a member of a London gang of street thugs. In 2006, he appeared in ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'', appearing in the early flashback scenes as [[Edward Norton]]'s character, Eduard Abramovicz, as a teenager. The scenes show the young Eduard as he first learns magic, and to do this, Johnson had to learn how to perform the ball trick displayed by his character. He learned how to perform the balancing of the egg on the stick, although that was effected mechanically.<ref>Writer/director [[Neil Burger]] explains this on the film's DVD commentary.</ref> Also in 2006, he starred in the film ''[[The Thief Lord (film)|The Thief Lord]]'', as Prosper.\n[[File:Aaron Taylor-Johnson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Johnson at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla'']]'']]\nTaylor-Johnson appeared as [[John Lennon]] in the 2009 biographical film film ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', directed by [[Sam Taylor-Wood]]. His performance saw him receive the [[Empire Award for Best Newcomer]] and he was also nominated for [[London Film Critics Circle Awards 2009#Young British Performer of the Year|Young British Performer of the Year]] by the [[London Film Critics' Circle]]. In 2010, Taylor-Johnson appeared as [[Kick-Ass (character)|David \"Dave\" Lizewski/Kick-Ass]], the lead character in ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'', based on the [[Kick-Ass (comic)|superhero comic book of the same name]] by Scottish writer [[Mark Millar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/43367 |title=Ain't It Cool News: The best in movie, TV, DVD, and comic book news |publisher=Aintitcool.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gholson|first=John |url=http://www.scifisquad.com/2009/12/14/kick-ass-kicks-ass-at-bnat|title='Kick-Ass' Kicks Ass at BNAT \u2013 The Moviefone Blog|publisher=Scifisquad.com|date=2 May 2011|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> His performance in ''Kick-Ass'' saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]. He has also appeared as the central character, William, in [[Hideo Nakata]]'s ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline/> In December 2010, Taylor-Johnson joined the cast of ''[[Albert Nobbs]]'' as a replacement for [[Orlando Bloom]], who dropped out of the production due to his wife's pregnancy.<ref name=nobbs>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|url=http://www.thewrap.com/node/23054|title=Aaron Johnson Joins Mia Wasikowska in 'Albert Nobbs'|publisher=Thewrap.com|date=6 December 2010|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in [[R.E.M.]]'s 2011 music video \"[[\u00dcberlin]]\", which was also directed by his then-fianc\u00e9e.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2011/mar/02/rem-uberlin|title=Watch REM's Uberlin, starring Aaron Johnson \u2013 video|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=4 December 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Taylor-Johnson played Count Vronsky in ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''. Later that year, he starred as Ben in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''. [[HitFix]] film critic Drew McWeeny was positive of the bond between Johnson and co-star [[Taylor Kitsch]], which \"seems not only credible but lived in and authentic throughout the film\", and noted the evolution in maturity of Johnson since ''Kick-Ass''.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny|first=Drew|title=Review: Oliver Stone turns Aaron Johnson, Taylor Kitsch, and Blake Lively into 'Savages'|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-oliver-stone-turns-aaron-johnson-taylor-kitsch-and-blake-lively-into-savages|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=30 June 2012}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in the ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' reboot, released in May 2014.<ref name=\"Godzilla1\">{{cite web|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |title=Elizabeth Olsen, Bryan Cranston circling 'Godzilla' |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=13 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313184951/http://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"Godzilla2\">{{cite web |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story |title='Godzilla' trailer: Bryan Cranston panics, destruction rains down |last=Gettell |first=Oliver |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=26 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226182729/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story#axzz2wDzJjMw7 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson played [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), the sequel to ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]''.<ref name=\"AgeofUltron\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |title=Official: Elizabeth Olsen & Aaron Taylor-Johnson Join 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' |publisher=Marvel |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=25 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108033705/http://marvel.com/news/movies/2013/11/25/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |archivedate=8 January 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson first appeared as the character in a post-credits scene of the film ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''.<ref name=\"WinterSoldier\">{{cite web|first=Jenna |last=Milly |date=14 March 2014 |title='Captain America: The Winter Soldier' premiere: Crossover is the word |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=15 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315010847/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |url-status=live  }}</ref> The role reunited him with [[Elizabeth Olsen]], who played his wife in ''Godzilla''.<ref name=\"Godzilla2\" /><ref name=\"AgeofUltron\" />\n\nIn 2016, he played Ray, a menacing Texan, in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''. For the role, he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]. Taylor-Johnson also became first Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor winner since [[Richard Benjamin]] who did not receive an [[Academy Award]] nomination. For the role he also received a nomination for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]. In 2017, he played an American soldier (alongside [[John Cena]]) in [[Doug Liman]]'s thriller ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson Eyed for Lead in Doug Liman's 'The Wall' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/aaron-taylor-johnson-the-wall-doug-liman-1201769484/|accessdate=1 December 2016|work=Variety|date=9 May 2016}}</ref> and in 2018, he appeared in ''[[Outlaw King]]'', a British-American historical action drama about [[Robert the Bruce]] and the Wars of Scottish Independence. In May 2019, Taylor-Johnson was cast in [[Christopher Nolan]]\u2019s ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'', set for release in July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/christopher-nolan-tenet-movie-cast-release-date-1202620596/|title=Christopher Nolan's New Movie Gets A Title, Final Cast As Shooting Begins|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, it was announced that Aaron Taylor Johnson will join [[Steve Pemberton]] on West End stage in [[The Pillowman]] play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/west-end-aaron-taylor-johnson-steve-pemberton-to-star-in-the-pillowman/|title=\nWest End: Aaron Taylor-Johnson & Steve Pemberton to Star in The Pillowman|publisher=Ikon London Magazine| first1 = Tamara|last1=Orlova-Alvarez | date=28 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> directed by Matthew Dunster.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sam Taylor-Wood & Aaron Johnson.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Taylor-Johnson, with Sam Taylor-Johnson, in September 2010]]\nAaron Johnson began a relationship with ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' director [[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]], after meeting on the 2009 set of the film when he was 18 and she was 42.<ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\"/> They announced their engagement in October 2009 and married at [[Babington House]], Somerset, England on 21 June 2012. The two changed their surnames to \"Taylor-Johnson\" and use the surname professionally.<ref name=\"Buchanan\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/aaron-johnson-sam-taylor-wood-marry.html |title=Aaron Johnson, Sam Taylor-Wood Marry |publisher=Vulture |accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20363616,00.html|title=She's Having His Baby!|magazine=People|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=25 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |title=50 Shades of Grey film to be directed by Sam Taylor-Johnson |work=Shepton Mallet Journal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522213458/http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |archivedate=22 May 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/6664818/Aaron-Johnson-fiance-of-artist-Sam-Taylor-Wood-considers-himself-a-very-lucky-man.html|title=Aaron Johnson, fianc\u00e9 of artist Sam Taylor-Wood, considers himself 'a very lucky man'|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=27 November 2009|accessdate=25 January 2012|location=London}}</ref> The couple have two daughters. He is also stepfather to two daughters from his wife's previous marriage.\n\nTaylor-Johnson was named one of [[GQ]]'s 50 best dressed British men in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 Best Dressed Men in Britain 2015 |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015/ |work=GQ |date=5 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107145128/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015 |archivedate=7 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Denotes works that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Apocalypse (2000 film)|The Apocalypse]]''\n| Johanan\n| Raffaele Mertes\n|\n|-\